-star expedition-cruise ship worldwide.\n\nThe ship was built in 1991. She specialises in trips to the [[Antarctic]]. She was built as ''Society Adventurer'', but was renamed when she was purchased by [[Hanseatic Tours]],{{when|date=April 2020}} as the fourth in a line of \"\"Hanseatics\". In 1997, [[Hapag-Lloyd]] purchased Hanseatic Tours, and she passed into their fleet.<ref name=\"simplonpc\" />\n\n==Career==\n\n=== ''Society Adventurer'' ===\n\nIn December 1989, the German cruise ship company [[Discoverer Reederei]] ordered a $75 million cruise ship from the Finnish shipbuilder [[Rauma Yards]] (formerly [[Rauma-Repola]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://meriteollisuus.teknologiateollisuus.fi/sites/meriteollisuus/files/inline-files/Meriteoll_historiikki_web.pdf|title=Kun rauta kelluu \u2014 V\u00e4l\u00e4hdyksi\u00e4 suomalaisen meriteollisuuden vuosisadasta|publisher=Meriteollisuus|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>) for its US-based subsidiary [[Society Expeditions]]. The ship, launched on 5 January 1991 as ''Society Adventurer'',<ref name=\"dnv\" /> was intended for adventure-style expedition cruises to remote destinations such as [[Antarctica]] and had, among other features, an ice-strengthened hull. However, when Discoverer Reederei was unable to take delivery of the vessel in the following summer due to financial troubles, the ownership was transferred to Rauma Yards's newly-established subsidiary Society Adventurer Shipping Company and the completed ship was laid up at the shipyard.<ref name=\"id\" /> During this time, ''Society Adventurer'' was inspected by a number of parties interested in acquiring the vessel, among them the future [[president of the United States]] [[Donald Trump]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ls24.fi/uutiset/donald-trump-kavi-raumalla-laivakaupoilla-nayttelijavaimo-naytti-poseeraamisen-mallia|title=Donald Trump k\u00e4vi Raumalla laivakaupoilla - n\u00e4yttelij\u00e4vaimo n\u00e4ytti poseeraamisen mallia|work=L\u00e4nsi-Suomi|date=21 May 2016|accessdate=4 April 2020|language=fi}}</ref>\n\n=== ''Hanseatic'' ===\n[[File:Hanseatic 5.jpg|thumb|left|''Hanseatic'' in Nuuk, Greenland, in 2008.]]\n\nIn 1993, the ship was first chartered and shortly afterwards purchased by the German expedition cruise operator [[Hanseatic Tours]].<ref name=\"id\" /> The company had been established two years earlier by [[Dirk Moldenhauer]], who had been the last captain of [[German Atlantic Line]]'s cruise ship [[TS Maxim Gorkiy|''Hanseatic'']] in 1973 and later acquired rights to the classic Hamburg Atlantic Line logo, livery and the name \"Hanseatic\".<ref name=\"simplonpc\">{{cite web|url=http://www.simplonpc.co.uk/HamburgAtlantik.html|title=Hamburg Atlantik Line/Deutsche Atlantik Line/Hanseatic Tours|accessdate=4 April 2020|author=Ian Boyle|work=Simplon Postcards}}</ref> ''Society Adventurer'' was renamed ''Hanseatic'' on 23 March 1993,<ref name=\"schwerdtner\">{{cite|title=German Luxury Ocean Liners: From Kaiser Wilhelm Der Grosse to Aidastella|last=Schwerdtner|first=Nils|publisher=Amberley Publishing|year=2013|}}</ref> becoming the fourth ship to bear the name, and the original blue-yellow-white Discoverer Reederei livery was replaced with the white hull and red decorative stripes.<ref name=\"id\" /> The vessel's maiden cruise from Hamburg to Sevilla began on 27 March 1993.<ref name=\"fof\">{{cite web|url=http://www.faktaomfartyg.se/society_adventurer_1991.htm|title=M/S Society Adventurer|work=Fakta om Fartyg|last=Asklander|first=Micke|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> When Hanseatic Tours was merged with [[Hapag-Lloyd Cruises]] in 1997, ''Hanseatic'' retained her original name as well as Hamburg Atlantic Line livery and funnel logo.<ref name=\"schwerdtner\" />\n\nBetween 1994 and 2013, ''Hanseatic'' transited the full length of the [[Northwest Passage]] 11 times, second only to the Russian [[icebreaker]] ''[[Kapitan Khlebnikov]]'' which is also used for expedition cruises.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spri.cam.ac.uk/resources/infosheets/northwestpassage.pdf|title=Transits of the Northwest Passage to the end of the 2019 navigation season|publisher=Scott Polar Research Institute|date=17 March 2020|accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== ''RCGS Resolute'' ===\n{{expand-section|date=April 2020}}\n\n''RCGS Resolute'' was scheduled to conduct a cruise to the Falkland Islands, South Georgia, and Antarctica from 19 October 2019, through 6 November 2019, beginning and ending in [[Ushuaia]], Tierra del Fuego Province, Argentina.  A medical emergency occurred on the ship while she was en route to Ushuaia, which delayed the ship, so the passengers were flown to Buenos Aires to meet the ship.  The ship sailed from Buenos Aires on 19 October.  On 22 October, the ship entered the port at Puerto Madryn to refuel.  After sitting in port for two days, it was revealed that the fuel could not be obtained because of non-payment by the ship operator, One Ocean Expeditions.  The Antarctic expedition was cancelled and the ship sailed back to Buenos Aires with all her passengers.  Once in Buenos Aires, the passengers disembarked and were left on their own with no reimbursement or compensation.  The ship was subsequently arrested in Buenos Aires for non-payment of debts. <ref>https://www.vesseltracker.com/en/Ships/Rcgs-Resolute-9000168.html</ref> <ref>https://www.oneoceanexpeditions.com/dates-and-rates</ref>\n\n== Incidents ==\n\n=== 1996 grounding ===\n{{expand-section|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 1997 grounding ===\n{{expand-section|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 2005 grounding ===\n{{expand-section|date=April 2020}}\n\n=== 2013 drydock fire ===\n\nOn 13 June 2013, the ship was in [[drydock]] at the Bredo Shipyard in [[Bremerhaven]], Germany when a fire broke out in the shipyard. This caused a delay in drydock and additional repairs were required and so the 17 June and 4 July sailings were cancelled.\n\n=== 2020 collision with Venezuelan patrol boat ''Naiguat\u00e1'' ===\nIn the early hours of 30 March 2020 ''RCGS Resolute'' was drifting  in International waters, near Willemstad, Curacao, some 60 miles off the country's northern coast, when the Venezuelan Coast Guard patrol boat  {{ship|Venezuelan patrol boat|Naiguat\u00e1||2}}, also known by her hull number GC-23, approached her. The Venezuelan ship ordered the cruise ship to follow her to Puerto Moreno on Isla De Margarita, located to the east, accusing her of violating the country's territorial waters. Gun shots were fired and, shortly thereafter, the navy vessel approached the starboard side at speed with an angle of 135\u00b0 and purposely collided with ''RCGS Resolute''. The navy vessel continued to ram the starboard bow in an apparent attempt to turn the ship's head towards Venezuelan territorial waters. While ''RCGS Resolute'' sustained minor damages, not affecting vessel's seaworthiness, the navy vessel suffered severe damage while making contact with the [[ice class|ice-strengthened]] [[bulbous bow]] of the expedition cruise vessel ''RCGS Resolute'' and started to take water.<ref name=jpost20200403>{{cite news |url=https://www.jpost.com/International/Venezuelan-warship-shoots-rams-into-German-cruise-vessel-before-sinking-623422 |title=Venezuelan warship shoots, rams into German cruise vessel before sinking |work=[[Jerusalem Post]] |date=3 April 2020 |access-date=3 April 2020 }}</ref> Ultimately ''Naiguat\u00e1'' sank, leaving the 44 naval personnel to be rescued by another vessel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fleetmon.com/maritime-news/2020/29297/cruise-ship-sunk-venezuelan-navy-ship-and-fled-pro/?fbclid=|title=Cruise Ship Sunk Venezuelan Navy Ship after being Fired at and Rammed. Don\u2019t mess with Resolute.|last=Voytenko|first=Mikhail|date=1 April 2020|website=Fleet Mon|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2 April 2020}}</ref>{{Better source|date=April 2020|reason=Non-NPOV}}<ref name=jpost20200403/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|IMO 9000168}}\n* [http://www.rcgsresolute.com/ RCGS Resolute Virtual Tour]<ref>{{cite web |title=One Ocean Dates and Rates |url=https://www.oneoceanexpeditions.com/dates-and-rates}}</ref>\n\n{{Hapag-Lloyd Cruises}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:RCGS Resolute}}\n[[Category:1991 ships]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Rauma, Finland]]\n[[Category:Cruise ships]]\n\n{{cruise-ship-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tupsumato", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1996 grounding:include source - I have to continue working on this later", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RCGS_Resolute"}
{"title_page": "Unification of Nepal", "text_new": "{{original research|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{POV|date=August 2012}}\n}}\n[[File:Gorkha3.jpg|thumb|Gorkhali soldiers in the Kathmandu palace courtyard]]\n\nBefore the [[Shah dynasty]] united Nepal, only [[Kathmandu]] was known as Nepal or [[Nepal Mandala]]. After conquering all the small kingdoms of Nepal in the mid-eighteenth century, King [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]] moved his capital to Kathmandu from [[Gorkha Kingdom|Gorkha]] and named the newly created empire, Nepal.\n\n==Establishment of expanded Gorkha kingdom==\nGorkha was a very small hilly kingdom with little wealth. After Prithvi Narayan Shah became king on 25 Chaitra 1799 BS, he started unification of Nepal. He began his campaign from America\n\n==Invasion of Nuwakot==\n[[Nara Bhupal Shah]], Prithvi Narayan Shah's father, had already tried to invade [[Nuwakot, Bagmati|Nuwakot]] in 1794 [[Vikram Samvat|B.S.]] during his reign, and failed. At that time, Nuwakot was under the administrative control of Kantipur (today known as [[Kathmandu]]). Kantipur supported Nuwakot against the invasion. Following his defeat, Nara Bhupal Shah gave up his efforts and handed the administrative power over to [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]] and Chandraprabhawati (the eldest queen of Nara Bhupal Shah). YO YO Honeysingh Shah died in 1799 B.S. and Prithivi Narayan Shah ascended to the throne on 25 Chaitra 1799 B.S.\n\nNuwakot was the trade route between Tibet and Kathmandu, and the western gateway to Kathmandu valley. Prithvi Narayan Shah sent Gorkhali troops, under Kaji Biraj Thapa, to attack Nuwakot. Biraj Thapa waited at Khinchet by the side of [[Trishuli River]] for an appropriate time to launch the attack. Prithvi Narayan Shah didn't like the strategy of Biraj Thapa and began to mistrust him following the report by Maheshwor Panta. So, he sent another Gorkhali battlegroup under Maheshwor Panta. The troops under Maheshwor Panta were defeated.\n\n[[File:Bamshidhar Kalu Pande.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Kalu Pande]] wearing [[Khukuri]], a [[Pande family|Pande Chhetri]] aristocrat; [[Kaji (Nepal)|Kaji]] (Prime Minister and Army Chief) of [[Gorkha Kingdom]].]]Kalu Pande was made the Commander-in-Chief of the Gorkhali Army after [[Biraj Thapa Magar]] and his first major Battle was the [[Battle of Kirtipur]]. Despite his initial resentment to the fact that the valley kings were well prepared and the Gorkhalis were not, Pande gave a 'Yes' to the operation, due to being insisted by [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]]. The Gorkhalis had set up a base on Naikap, a hill on the valley's western rim, from where they were to mount their assaults on Kirtipur. They were armed with swords, bows and arrows and [[musket]]s.<ref>Vansittart, Eden (1896). ''Notes on Nepal''. Asian Educational Services. {{ISBN|978-81-206-0774-3}}. Page 34.</ref>\n\nThe Valley Kings brought a large number of Doyas from Indian Plains under Shaktiballabh sardar. During the first assault in 1757, the Gorkhali army killed 1200 enemies, mostly Doyas, but were badly beaten themselves. Both sides suffered heavy losses. As they advanced towards Kirtipur, the combined force of Valley Kings under Kaji Gangadhar Jha, Kaji Gangaram Thapa and Sardar Shaktiballabh brought Havoc to the outnumbered Gorkhalis. The two forces fought on the plain of Tyangla Phant in the northwest of [[Kirtipur]]. Surapratap Shah, the King's brother lost his right eye to an arrow while scaling the city wall. The Gorkhali commander Kaji Kalu Pande was surrounded and killed, and the Gorkhali king himself narrowly escaped with his life into the surrounding hills disguised as a [[saint]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Majupuria |first=Trilok Chandra |title=Kirtipur: The Ancient Town on the Hill |url=http://www.nepal-traveller.com/index.php?action=articledetail&id=259 |accessdate=18 October 2012 |newspaper=Nepal Traveller |date=March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Wright |first=Daniel |authorlink= |coauthors= |url=https://archive.org/stream/HistoryOfNepal/HistoryOfNepaldanielWright#page/n269/mode/2up |title=History of Nepal |work= |publisher=New Delhi: Asian Educational Services |year=1990 |accessdate=7 November 2012}} Page 227.</ref>\n\nAfter his conquest of the Kathmandu Valley, Prithvi Narayan Shah conquered other smaller territories south of the valley to keep other smaller fiefdoms near his Gurkha state out of the influence and control of British rule. After his kingdom spread from north to south, he made Kantipur the capital of expanded country, which was then known as Kingdom of Gorkha (Gorkha Samrajya).<ref name=\"Bindloss2010\">{{cite book|author=Joseph Bindloss|title=Nepal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wiIw2_WFwC4C&pg=PA37|date=15 September 2010|publisher=Lonely Planet Publications|isbn=978-1-74220-361-4|page=37}}</ref><ref>[http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2016-02-28/less-of-a-hero.html Less of a hero]</ref>\n\n==Shifting capital==\nPrithvi Narayan Shah in his Dibya Upadesh suggested a shift of the capital from Gorkha Durbar to Nepal.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lawcommission.gov.np/en/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/dibbaya-upadesh-of-prithivi-narayan-shah.pdf | title=Nepal Law Commission Dibya Upadesh}}</ref> The expanded Gorkha kingdom was renamed with the name of its capital.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://eap.bl.uk/archive-file/EAP272-1-1-1152 | title=Nep\u0101la Ki? Gorash\u0101 |year=1955}}</ref>\n\n==Battle of Kirtipur==\n{{Main|Battle of Kirtipur}}\n[[File:Gorkha3.jpg|thumb|Gorkhali soldiers preparing war against Kathmandu Valley]]\nDespite his initial resentment of Kaji [[Kalu Pande]] that the valley kings were well prepared and the Gorkhalis were not, Pande agreed for battle against the Kingdom of [[Kirtipur]] in the [[Kathmandu valley]] on being insisted from the monarch [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]]. The Gorkhalis had set up a base on Naikap to mount their assaults on Kirtipur. They were armed with swords, bows and arrows and [[musket]]s.<ref>Vansittart, Eden (1896). ''Notes on Nepal''. Asian Educational Services. {{ISBN|978-81-206-0774-3}}. Page 34.</ref>\nThe two forces fought on the plain of Tyangla Phant in the northwest of [[Kirtipur]]. Surapratap Shah, the King's brother lost his right eye to an arrow while scaling the city wall. The Gorkhali commander Kaji [[Kalu Pande]] was surrounded and killed, and the Gorkhali king himself narrowly escaped with his life into the surrounding hills disguised as a [[saint]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Majupuria |first=Trilok Chandra |title=Kirtipur: The Ancient Town on the Hill |url=http://www.nepal-traveller.com/index.php?action=articledetail&id=259 |accessdate=18 October 2012 |newspaper=Nepal Traveller |date=March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117014432/http://www.nepal-traveller.com/index.php?action=articledetail&id=259 |archive-date=17 November 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Wright |first=Daniel |authorlink= |coauthors= |url=https://archive.org/stream/HistoryOfNepal/HistoryOfNepaldanielWright#page/n269/mode/2up |title=History of Nepal |work= |publisher=New Delhi: Asian Educational Services |year=1990 |accessdate=7 November 2012}} Page 227.</ref> In 1767, the King of Gorkha Prithvi Narayan sent his army to attack Kirtipur a third time under the command of Surpratap. In response, the three kings of valley joined forces and sent their troops to the relief of Kirtipur, but they could not dislodge the Gorkhalis from their positions. A noble of Lalitpur named Danuvanta crossed over to Shah's side and treacherously let the Gorkhalis into the town.<ref name=\"Kirkpatrick 1811\">{{cite book | last = Kirkpatrick| first = Colonel| authorlink = | coauthors = | url = https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_ijxAAAAAYAAJ| title = An Account of the Kingdom of Nepaul| work = | publisher = London: William Miller| year=1811| accessdate = 17 October 2012}} Pages 382-386.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title= The city of good deeds |url= http://nepalitimes.com/issue/18/Culture/9018|accessdate=18 October 2012|newspaper= Nepali Times |date=24\u201330 November 2000}}</ref>\n\n===Annexation of Makwanpur & Hariharpur===\nKing Digbardhan Sen and his minister Kanak Singh Baniya had already sent their families to safer grounds before the encirclement of their fortress. The Gorkhalis launched an attack on 21 August 1762. The battle lasted for eight hours. King Digbardhan and his minister Kanak Singh escaped to Hariharpur Gadhi. Makawanpur was thus annexed to Nepal.<ref name=\"nepalarmy\"/>\n\nAfter occupying the Makawanpur Gadhi fort, the Gorkhali forces started planning for an attack on Hariharpur Gadhi, a strategic fort on a mountain ridge of the Mahabharat range, also south of Kathmandu. It controlled the route to the Kathmandu valley. At the dusk of 4 October 1762, the Gorkhalis launched the attack. The soldiers at Hariharpur Gadhi fought valiantly against the Gorkha forces, but were ultimately forced to vacate the Gadhi after mid-night. About 500 soldiers of Hariharpur died in the battle.<ref name=\"nepalarmy\"/> Mir Qasim, the [[Nawabs of Bengal and Murshidabad|Nawab of Bengal]] extended his help to kings of Kathmandu valley with his forces to attack the Gorkhali forces. On 20 January 1763, Gorkhali commander [[Vamsharaj Pande]] won the battle against [[Mir Qasim]].<ref name=\"army\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nepalarmy.mil.np/history.php?page=two|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607215048/http://www.nepalarmy.mil.np/history.php?page=two|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 June 2011|title=History of the Nepalese Army|publisher=Nepalese Army|accessdate=7 October 2016}}</ref> Similarly, Captain Kinloch of British East India Company also extended his support by sending contingents against Gorkhalis. King Prithvi Narayan sent Kaji [[Vamsharaj Pande]], [[Naahar Singh Basnyat]], Jeeva Shah, Ram Krishna Kunwar and others to defeat the forces of [[Gurgin Khan]] at Makwanpur.{{sfn|Vaidya|1993|p=180}}{{sfn|Hamal|1995|p=202}}\n\n===Conquest of Kathmandu valley and Declaration of Kingdom of Nepal===\n{{Main|Battle of Kathmandu|Battle of Lalitpur|Battle of Bhaktapur}}\n[[File:Ram Krishna Kunwar.jpg|thumb|''[[Sardar]]'' [[Ram Krishna Kunwar]], senior military commander of Gorkhali forces]]\nThe victory in the Battle of Kirtipur climaxed Shah's two-decade-long effort to take possession of the wealthy Kathmandu Valley. After the fall of Kirtipur, Shah took the other cities [[Kathmandu]] and Lalitpur in 1768 and [[Bhaktapur]] in 1769, completing his conquest of the valley.<ref name=\"Kirkpatrick 1811\"/> In a letter to [[Ram Krishna Kunwar]], King Prithvi Narayan Shah was unhappy at the death of Kaji [[Kalu Pande]] in [[Kirtipur]] and thought it was impossible to conquer [[Kathmandu valley]] after the death of Kalu Pande.{{sfn|Vaidya|1993|p=151}} After the annexation of Kathmandu valley, King [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]] praised in his letter about valour and wisdom shown by Ramkrishna in annexation of Kathmandu, Lalitpur and Bhaktapur (i.e. Nepal valley at the time) on 1768-69 A.D.{{sfn|Regmi|1972|p=95}} Similarly,  [[Vamsharaj Pande]], Kalu Pande's eldest son, was the army commander who led attack of Gorkhali side on the [[Battle of Bhaktapur]] on 14 April 1769 A.D.{{sfn|Vaidya|1993|p=163}}\n\n===Conquest of Kirant country===\n[[File:Abhiman Singh Basnyat.jpg|thumb|''[[Mulkaji]]'' [[Abhiman Singh Basnyat]], a military commander and later [[Mulkaji|Chief Minister (Mulkaji)]]]]\nKing [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]] had deployed ''[[Sardar]]'' [[Ram Krishna Kunwar]] to the invasion of [[Kirant]] regional areas comprising; Pallo Kirant (Limbuwan), Wallo Kirant and Majh Kirant (Khambuwan).{{sfn|Hamal|1995|p=180}} In 13th of Bhadra 1829 [[Vikram Samvat]] (i.e. 29 August 1772), Ram Krishna crossed [[Koshi river|Dudhkoshi]] river to invade King Karna Sen of Kirant and Saptari region{{sfn|Regmi|1972|p=95}} with fellow commander [[Abhiman Singh Basnyat]].{{sfn|Vaidya|1993|p=165}} He crossed [[Arun River, China-Nepal|Arun River]] to reach [[Chainpur, Kosi|Chainpur]].{{sfn|Vaidya|1993|p=167}} Later, he achieved victory over Kirant region.{{sfn|Hamal|1995|p=181}} King Prithvi Narayan Shah bestowed 22 pairs of Shirpau (special headgear) in appreciation to Ram Krishna Kunwar after his victory over the Kirant region.{{sfn|Hamal|1995|p=181}}\n\n===Political Conflicts ===\nOn 1775, the conqueror king [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]], who expanded [[Gorkha Kingdom]] to the Kingdom of Nepal died at Nuwakot.{{sfn|Bibhag|1990|p=73}} [[Swarup Singh Karki]], a shrewd Gorkhali courtier from a [[Chhetri]] family of Eastern Nepal,{{sfn|Singh|1997|p=142}} marched with army to Nuwakot to confine Prince [[Bahadur Shah of Nepal]] who was then mourning the death of his father former King [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]].{{sfn|Bibhag|1990|p=73}} He confined Bahadur Shah and Prince [[Dal Mardan Shah]] with consent from newly reigning King [[Pratap Singh Shah]] who was considered to have no distinction of right and wrong.{{sfn|Bibhag|1990|p=73}} In the annual Pajani (renewal) of that year, Swarup Singh was promoted to the position of [[Kaji (Nepal)|Kaji]] along with [[Abhiman Singh Basnyat]], [[Amar Singh Thapa]] and Parashuram Thapa.{{sfn|Bibhag|1990|p=73}} In [[Falgun]] 1832 [[Bikram Samvat|B.S.]], he succeeded in exiling Bahadur Shah, Dal Mardan Shah and Guru Gajraj Mishra on three heinous charges.{{sfn|Bibhag|1990|p=74}} The reign of King Pratap Singh was characterized by the constant rivalry between Swarup and [[Vamsharaj Pande]], a member of the leading [[Pande family (Nepal)|Pande family]] of Gorkha.{{sfn|Shaha|1990|p=43}} The document dated [[Bikram Samvat]] 1833 [[Bhadra]] Vadi 3 Roj 6 (i.e. Friday 2 August 1776), shows that he had carried the title of [[Dewan]] along with Vamsharaj Pande.{{sfn|D.R. Regmi|1975|p=272}} King [[Pratap Singh Shah]] died on 22 November 1777 A.D.{{sfn|Karmacharya|2005|p=36}} leaving his infant son [[Rana Bahadur Shah]] as the [[King of Nepal]].{{sfn|D.R. Regmi|1975|p=285}} [[Sarbajit Rana Magar]] was made a [[Kaji (Nepal)|Kaji]] along with [[Balbhadra Shah]] and [[Vamsharaj Pande]]{{sfn|Shaha|1990|p=46}} while Daljit Shah was chosen as Chief Chautariya.{{sfn|D.R. Regmi|1975|p=285}}{{sfn|Shaha|1990|p=46}} Historian [[Dilli Raman Regmi]] asserts that Sarbajit was chosen as  [[Mulkaji|Chief Kazi]] (equivalent to [[Prime Minister of Nepal]]).{{sfn|D.R. Regmi|1975|p=285}} Historian [[Rishikesh Shah]] asserts that Sarbajit was the head of the Nepalese government for a short period in 1778.{{sfn|Shaha|2001|p=21}} Afterwards, rivalry arose between Prince [[Bahadur Shah of Nepal]] and [[Queen Rajendra of Nepal|Queen Rajendra Laxmi]]. In the rivalry, Sarbajit led the followers of the Queen opposed to Sriharsh Pant who led the followers of Bahadur Shah.<ref name=\"himalaya\">{{cite web|url=http://himalaya.socanth.cam.ac.uk/collections/journals/ancientnepal/pdf/ancient_nepal_121-122_01.pdf |title=Journal |website=himalaya.socanth.cam.ac.uk |format=PDF}}</ref> The group of Bharadars (officers) led by Sarbajit poisoned the ears of Rajendra Laxmi against Bahadur Shah.{{sfn|Rana|1978|p=6}} Rajendra Laxmi succeeded in the confinement of Prince Bahadur Shah with the help of her new minister Sarbajit.{{sfn|Mahesh Chandra Regmi|1975|p=214}} Guru Gajraj Mishra came to rescue Bahadur Shah on the condition that Bahadur Shah should leave the country.{{sfn|Mahesh Chandra Regmi|1975|p=214}}{{sfn|T.U. History Association|1977|p=5}} Also, his rival Sriharsh Pant was branded outcast and expelled instead of execution which was prohibited for [[Brahmin]]s.<ref name=\"himalaya\"/>\n\nPrince Bahadur Shah confined his sister-in-law Queen Rajendra Laxmi on the charge of having illicit relation with Sarbajit{{sfn|Regmi|1975|p=215}} on 31 August 1778.{{sfn|Karmacharya|2005|p=36}}{{sfn|D.R. Regmi|1975|p=294}}{{sfn|Bajracharya|1992|p=21}} Subsequently, Sarbajit was executed inside the palace by Prince Bahadur Shah{{sfn|Mahesh Chandra Regmi|1975|p=215}}{{sfn|Puratattva Bibhag|1990|p=76}} with the help of male servants of the royal palace.{{sfn|Mahesh Chandra Regmi|1975|p=215}} Historian Bhadra Ratna Bajracharya asserts that it was actually Chautariya Daljit Shah who led the opposing group against Sarbajit Rana and Rajendra Laxmi.{{sfn|Bajracharya|1992|pp=21-22}} The letter dated [[Bikram Samvat|B.S.]] 1835 [[Bhadra (Nepali calendar)|Bhadra]] Sudi 11 Roj 4 (1778 A.D.) to Narayan Malla and Vrajabasi Pande asserts the death of Sarbajit under misconduct and the appointment of Bahadur Shah as [[regent]].{{sfn|Karmacharya|2005|p=36}} The death of Sarbajit Rana Magar is considered to have marked the initiation of court conspiracies and massacres in the newly unified Kingdom of Nepal.{{sfn|T.U. History Association|1977|p=5}} Historian [[Baburam Acharya]] points that the sanctions against Queen Rajendra Laxmi under moral misconduct was a mistake of Bahadur Shah. Similarly, the murder of Sarbajit was condemned by many historians as an act of injustice.{{sfn|Bajracharya|1992|p=22}}\n\n[[Vamsharaj Pande]], once Dewan of Nepal and son of the popular commander [[Kalu Pande]], was beheaded on the conspiracy of [[Queen Rajendra of Nepal|Queen Rajendra Laxmi]] with his support.{{sfn|Karmacharya|2005|p=46}}{{sfn|Shaha|2001|p=62}} In the special tribunal meeting at Bhandarkhal garden, east of Kathmandu Durbar, Swaroop Singh held Vamsharaj liable for letting the King of Parbat, Kirtibam Malla to run away in the battle a year ago.{{sfn|Bajracharya|1992|p=35}} He had a fiery conversation with Vamsharaj before Vamsharaj was declared guilty and was subsequently executed by beheading on the tribunal.<ref name=\"himalaya\"/> Historian [[Rishikesh Shah]] and Ganga Karmacharya claim that he was executed on March 1785.{{sfn|Karmacharya|2005|p=46}}{{sfn|Shaha|2001|p=62}} Bhadra Ratna Bajracharya and Tulsi Ram Vaidya claim that he was executed on 21 April 1785.{{sfn|Bajracharya|1992|p=35}}<ref name=\"himalaya\"/> On 2 July 1785, his stiff opponent Prince Regent [[Bahadur Shah of Nepal]] was arrested and on the eleventh day of imprisonment on 13 July, his only supporter Queen Rajendra Laxmi died.{{sfn|Karmacharya|2005|p=46}}{{sfn|Shaha|2001|p=62}} Then onwards, Bahadur Shah took over the regency of his nephew King [[Rana Bahadur Shah]]{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=10}} and on the first moments of his regency ordered Swaroop Singh who was in [[Pokhara]] to be beheaded there {{sfn|Bibhag|1990|p=77}}{{sfn|Shaha|2001|p=63}} on the charges of [[treason]].{{sfn|Hamal|1995|p=81}} He had gone to Kaski to join Daljit Shah's military campaign of Kaski fearing retaliation of the old courtiers due to his conspiracy against Vamsharaj. He was executed on 24th [[Shrawan (Nepali calendar)|Shrawan]] 1842 [[Bikram Samvat|B.S]].{{sfn|Bibhag|1990|p=77}}\n\n===Tibetan conflict===\n{{See|Sino-Nepalese War}}\n[[File:Battle of Jhunga.jpg|thumb|Battle of Jhunga in 1788 A.D., Nepali forces (in black) achieved victory against Tibetan forces (in red & yellow)]]\nAfter the death of Prithvi Narayan Shah, the Shah dynasty began to expand their kingdom into what is present day North India. Between 1788 and 1791, Nepal invaded Tibet and robbed [[Tashi Lhunpo Monastery]] of [[Shigatse]]. Tibet sought Chinese help and the [[Qianlong Emperor]] of the Chinese [[Qing Dynasty]] appointed [[Fuk'anggan]] commander-in-chief of the Tibetan campaign. Heavy damages were inflicted on both sides. The Nepali forces retreated step by step back to Nuwakot to stretch Sino-Tibetan forces uncomfortably. Chinese launched uphill attack during the daylight and failed to succeed due to strong counterattack with [[Khukuri]] at Nuwakot.<ref name=\"nepalarmythree\"/> The Chinese army suffered a major setback when they tried to cross a monsoon-flooded Betrawati, close to the Gorkhali palace in Nuwakot.<ref>Stiller, L.F., \"The Rise of the House of Gorkha.\" Patna Jesuit Society. Patna. 1975.</ref> A stalemate ensued when [[Fuk'anggan]] was keen to protect his troops and wanted to negotiate at Nuwakot. The treaty was favouring more to Chinese side where Nepal had to send tributes to the Chinese emperor.<ref name=\"nepalarmythree\"/>\n\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of Nepal]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Fr. Giuseppe. (1799). ''An account of the kingdom of Nepal''. Asiatic Researches. Vol 2. (1799). pp. 307\u2013322.\n* Reed, David. (2002). ''The Rough Guide to Nepal''. DK Publishing, Inc.\n* Wright, Daniel, ''History of Nepal''. New Delhi-Madras, Asian Educational Services, 1990\n\n{{Nepal topics}}\n[[Category:History of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Gurkhas]]\n[[Category:National unifications]]\n", "text_old": "{{original research|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{Refimprove|date=December 2009}}\n{{POV|date=August 2012}}\n}}\n[[File:Gorkha3.jpg|thumb|Gorkhali soldiers in the Kathmandu palace courtyard]]\n\nBefore the [[Shah dynasty]] united Nepal, only [[Kathmandu]] was known as Nepal or [[Nepal Mandala]]. After conquering all the small kingdoms of Nepal in the mid-eighteenth century, King [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]] moved his capital to Kathmandu from [[Gorkha Kingdom|Gorkha]] and named the newly created empire, Nepal.\n\n==Establishment of expanded Gorkha kingdom==\nGorkha was a small hilly kingdom with little wealth. After Prithvi Narayan Shah became king on 25 Chaitra 1799 BS, he started unification of Nepal. He began his campaign from Nuwakot.\n\n==Invasion of Nuwakot==\n[[Nara Bhupal Shah]], Prithvi Narayan Shah's father, had already tried to invade [[Nuwakot, Bagmati|Nuwakot]] in 1794 [[Vikram Samvat|B.S.]] during his reign, and failed. At that time, Nuwakot was under the administrative control of Kantipur (today known as [[Kathmandu]]). Kantipur supported Nuwakot against the invasion. Following his defeat, Nara Bhupal Shah gave up his efforts and handed the administrative power over to [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]] and Chandraprabhawati (the eldest queen of Nara Bhupal Shah). Nara Bhupal Shah died in 1799 B.S. and Prithivi Narayan Shah ascended to the throne on 25 Chaitra 1799 B.S.\n\nNuwakot was the trade route between Tibet and Kathmandu, and the western gateway to Kathmandu valley. Prithvi Narayan Shah sent Gorkhali troops, under Kaji Biraj Thapa, to attack Nuwakot. Biraj Thapa waited at Khinchet by the side of [[Trishuli River]] for an appropriate time to launch the attack. Prithvi Narayan Shah didn't like the strategy of Biraj Thapa and began to mistrust him following the report by Maheshwor Panta. So, he sent another Gorkhali battlegroup under Maheshwor Panta. The troops under Maheshwor Panta were defeated.\n\n[[File:Bamshidhar Kalu Pande.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Kalu Pande]] wearing [[Khukuri]], a [[Pande family|Pande Chhetri]] aristocrat; [[Kaji (Nepal)|Kaji]] (Prime Minister and Army Chief) of [[Gorkha Kingdom]].]]Kalu Pande was made the Commander-in-Chief of the Gorkhali Army after [[Biraj Thapa Magar]] and his first major Battle was the [[Battle of Kirtipur]]. Despite his initial resentment to the fact that the valley kings were well prepared and the Gorkhalis were not, Pande gave a 'Yes' to the operation, due to being insisted by [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]]. The Gorkhalis had set up a base on Naikap, a hill on the valley's western rim, from where they were to mount their assaults on Kirtipur. They were armed with swords, bows and arrows and [[musket]]s.<ref>Vansittart, Eden (1896). ''Notes on Nepal''. Asian Educational Services. {{ISBN|978-81-206-0774-3}}. Page 34.</ref>\n\nThe Valley Kings brought a large number of Doyas from Indian Plains under Shaktiballabh sardar. During the first assault in 1757, the Gorkhali army killed 1200 enemies, mostly Doyas, but were badly beaten themselves. Both sides suffered heavy losses. As they advanced towards Kirtipur, the combined force of Valley Kings under Kaji Gangadhar Jha, Kaji Gangaram Thapa and Sardar Shaktiballabh brought Havoc to the outnumbered Gorkhalis. The two forces fought on the plain of Tyangla Phant in the northwest of [[Kirtipur]]. Surapratap Shah, the King's brother lost his right eye to an arrow while scaling the city wall. The Gorkhali commander Kaji Kalu Pande was surrounded and killed, and the Gorkhali king himself narrowly escaped with his life into the surrounding hills disguised as a [[saint]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Majupuria |first=Trilok Chandra |title=Kirtipur: The Ancient Town on the Hill |url=http://www.nepal-traveller.com/index.php?action=articledetail&id=259 |accessdate=18 October 2012 |newspaper=Nepal Traveller |date=March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Wright |first=Daniel |authorlink= |coauthors= |url=https://archive.org/stream/HistoryOfNepal/HistoryOfNepaldanielWright#page/n269/mode/2up |title=History of Nepal |work= |publisher=New Delhi: Asian Educational Services |year=1990 |accessdate=7 November 2012}} Page 227.</ref>\n\nAfter his conquest of the Kathmandu Valley, Prithvi Narayan Shah conquered other smaller territories south of the valley to keep other smaller fiefdoms near his Gurkha state out of the influence and control of British rule. After his kingdom spread from north to south, he made Kantipur the capital of expanded country, which was then known as Kingdom of Gorkha (Gorkha Samrajya).<ref name=\"Bindloss2010\">{{cite book|author=Joseph Bindloss|title=Nepal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wiIw2_WFwC4C&pg=PA37|date=15 September 2010|publisher=Lonely Planet Publications|isbn=978-1-74220-361-4|page=37}}</ref><ref>[http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/printedition/news/2016-02-28/less-of-a-hero.html Less of a hero]</ref>\n\n==Shifting capital==\nPrithvi Narayan Shah in his Dibya Upadesh suggested a shift of the capital from Gorkha Durbar to Nepal.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lawcommission.gov.np/en/wp-content/uploads/2018/09/dibbaya-upadesh-of-prithivi-narayan-shah.pdf | title=Nepal Law Commission Dibya Upadesh}}</ref> The expanded Gorkha kingdom was renamed with the name of its capital.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://eap.bl.uk/archive-file/EAP272-1-1-1152 | title=Nep\u0101la Ki? Gorash\u0101 |year=1955}}</ref>\n\n==Battle of Kirtipur==\n{{Main|Battle of Kirtipur}}\n[[File:Gorkha3.jpg|thumb|Gorkhali soldiers preparing war against Kathmandu Valley]]\nDespite his initial resentment of Kaji [[Kalu Pande]] that the valley kings were well prepared and the Gorkhalis were not, Pande agreed for battle against the Kingdom of [[Kirtipur]] in the [[Kathmandu valley]] on being insisted from the monarch [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]]. The Gorkhalis had set up a base on Naikap to mount their assaults on Kirtipur. They were armed with swords, bows and arrows and [[musket]]s.<ref>Vansittart, Eden (1896). ''Notes on Nepal''. Asian Educational Services. {{ISBN|978-81-206-0774-3}}. Page 34.</ref>\nThe two forces fought on the plain of Tyangla Phant in the northwest of [[Kirtipur]]. Surapratap Shah, the King's brother lost his right eye to an arrow while scaling the city wall. The Gorkhali commander Kaji [[Kalu Pande]] was surrounded and killed, and the Gorkhali king himself narrowly escaped with his life into the surrounding hills disguised as a [[saint]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Majupuria |first=Trilok Chandra |title=Kirtipur: The Ancient Town on the Hill |url=http://www.nepal-traveller.com/index.php?action=articledetail&id=259 |accessdate=18 October 2012 |newspaper=Nepal Traveller |date=March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117014432/http://www.nepal-traveller.com/index.php?action=articledetail&id=259 |archive-date=17 November 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Wright |first=Daniel |authorlink= |coauthors= |url=https://archive.org/stream/HistoryOfNepal/HistoryOfNepaldanielWright#page/n269/mode/2up |title=History of Nepal |work= |publisher=New Delhi: Asian Educational Services |year=1990 |accessdate=7 November 2012}} Page 227.</ref> In 1767, the King of Gorkha Prithvi Narayan sent his army to attack Kirtipur a third time under the command of Surpratap. In response, the three kings of valley joined forces and sent their troops to the relief of Kirtipur, but they could not dislodge the Gorkhalis from their positions. A noble of Lalitpur named Danuvanta crossed over to Shah's side and treacherously let the Gorkhalis into the town.<ref name=\"Kirkpatrick 1811\">{{cite book | last = Kirkpatrick| first = Colonel| authorlink = | coauthors = | url = https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_ijxAAAAAYAAJ| title = An Account of the Kingdom of Nepaul| work = | publisher = London: William Miller| year=1811| accessdate = 17 October 2012}} Pages 382-386.</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=|first=|title= The city of good deeds |url= http://nepalitimes.com/issue/18/Culture/9018|accessdate=18 October 2012|newspaper= Nepali Times |date=24\u201330 November 2000}}</ref>\n\n===Annexation of Makwanpur & Hariharpur===\nKing Digbardhan Sen and his minister Kanak Singh Baniya had already sent their families to safer grounds before the encirclement of their fortress. The Gorkhalis launched an attack on 21 August 1762. The battle lasted for eight hours. King Digbardhan and his minister Kanak Singh escaped to Hariharpur Gadhi. Makawanpur was thus annexed to Nepal.<ref name=\"nepalarmy\"/>\n\nAfter occupying the Makawanpur Gadhi fort, the Gorkhali forces started planning for an attack on Hariharpur Gadhi, a strategic fort on a mountain ridge of the Mahabharat range, also south of Kathmandu. It controlled the route to the Kathmandu valley. At the dusk of 4 October 1762, the Gorkhalis launched the attack. The soldiers at Hariharpur Gadhi fought valiantly against the Gorkha forces, but were ultimately forced to vacate the Gadhi after mid-night. About 500 soldiers of Hariharpur died in the battle.<ref name=\"nepalarmy\"/> Mir Qasim, the [[Nawabs of Bengal and Murshidabad|Nawab of Bengal]] extended his help to kings of Kathmandu valley with his forces to attack the Gorkhali forces. On 20 January 1763, Gorkhali commander [[Vamsharaj Pande]] won the battle against [[Mir Qasim]].<ref name=\"army\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nepalarmy.mil.np/history.php?page=two|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607215048/http://www.nepalarmy.mil.np/history.php?page=two|url-status=dead|archive-date=7 June 2011|title=History of the Nepalese Army|publisher=Nepalese Army|accessdate=7 October 2016}}</ref> Similarly, Captain Kinloch of British East India Company also extended his support by sending contingents against Gorkhalis. King Prithvi Narayan sent Kaji [[Vamsharaj Pande]], [[Naahar Singh Basnyat]], Jeeva Shah, Ram Krishna Kunwar and others to defeat the forces of [[Gurgin Khan]] at Makwanpur.{{sfn|Vaidya|1993|p=180}}{{sfn|Hamal|1995|p=202}}\n\n===Conquest of Kathmandu valley and Declaration of Kingdom of Nepal===\n{{Main|Battle of Kathmandu|Battle of Lalitpur|Battle of Bhaktapur}}\n[[File:Ram Krishna Kunwar.jpg|thumb|''[[Sardar]]'' [[Ram Krishna Kunwar]], senior military commander of Gorkhali forces]]\nThe victory in the Battle of Kirtipur climaxed Shah's two-decade-long effort to take possession of the wealthy Kathmandu Valley. After the fall of Kirtipur, Shah took the other cities [[Kathmandu]] and Lalitpur in 1768 and [[Bhaktapur]] in 1769, completing his conquest of the valley.<ref name=\"Kirkpatrick 1811\"/> In a letter to [[Ram Krishna Kunwar]], King Prithvi Narayan Shah was unhappy at the death of Kaji [[Kalu Pande]] in [[Kirtipur]] and thought it was impossible to conquer [[Kathmandu valley]] after the death of Kalu Pande.{{sfn|Vaidya|1993|p=151}} After the annexation of Kathmandu valley, King [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]] praised in his letter about valour and wisdom shown by Ramkrishna in annexation of Kathmandu, Lalitpur and Bhaktapur (i.e. Nepal valley at the time) on 1768-69 A.D.{{sfn|Regmi|1972|p=95}} Similarly,  [[Vamsharaj Pande]], Kalu Pande's eldest son, was the army commander who led attack of Gorkhali side on the [[Battle of Bhaktapur]] on 14 April 1769 A.D.{{sfn|Vaidya|1993|p=163}}\n\n===Conquest of Kirant country===\n[[File:Abhiman Singh Basnyat.jpg|thumb|''[[Mulkaji]]'' [[Abhiman Singh Basnyat]], a military commander and later [[Mulkaji|Chief Minister (Mulkaji)]]]]\nKing [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]] had deployed ''[[Sardar]]'' [[Ram Krishna Kunwar]] to the invasion of [[Kirant]] regional areas comprising; Pallo Kirant (Limbuwan), Wallo Kirant and Majh Kirant (Khambuwan).{{sfn|Hamal|1995|p=180}} In 13th of Bhadra 1829 [[Vikram Samvat]] (i.e. 29 August 1772), Ram Krishna crossed [[Koshi river|Dudhkoshi]] river to invade King Karna Sen of Kirant and Saptari region{{sfn|Regmi|1972|p=95}} with fellow commander [[Abhiman Singh Basnyat]].{{sfn|Vaidya|1993|p=165}} He crossed [[Arun River, China-Nepal|Arun River]] to reach [[Chainpur, Kosi|Chainpur]].{{sfn|Vaidya|1993|p=167}} Later, he achieved victory over Kirant region.{{sfn|Hamal|1995|p=181}} King Prithvi Narayan Shah bestowed 22 pairs of Shirpau (special headgear) in appreciation to Ram Krishna Kunwar after his victory over the Kirant region.{{sfn|Hamal|1995|p=181}}\n\n===Political Conflicts ===\nOn 1775, the conqueror king [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]], who expanded [[Gorkha Kingdom]] to the Kingdom of Nepal died at Nuwakot.{{sfn|Bibhag|1990|p=73}} [[Swarup Singh Karki]], a shrewd Gorkhali courtier from a [[Chhetri]] family of Eastern Nepal,{{sfn|Singh|1997|p=142}} marched with army to Nuwakot to confine Prince [[Bahadur Shah of Nepal]] who was then mourning the death of his father former King [[Prithvi Narayan Shah]].{{sfn|Bibhag|1990|p=73}} He confined Bahadur Shah and Prince [[Dal Mardan Shah]] with consent from newly reigning King [[Pratap Singh Shah]] who was considered to have no distinction of right and wrong.{{sfn|Bibhag|1990|p=73}} In the annual Pajani (renewal) of that year, Swarup Singh was promoted to the position of [[Kaji (Nepal)|Kaji]] along with [[Abhiman Singh Basnyat]], [[Amar Singh Thapa]] and Parashuram Thapa.{{sfn|Bibhag|1990|p=73}} In [[Falgun]] 1832 [[Bikram Samvat|B.S.]], he succeeded in exiling Bahadur Shah, Dal Mardan Shah and Guru Gajraj Mishra on three heinous charges.{{sfn|Bibhag|1990|p=74}} The reign of King Pratap Singh was characterized by the constant rivalry between Swarup and [[Vamsharaj Pande]], a member of the leading [[Pande family (Nepal)|Pande family]] of Gorkha.{{sfn|Shaha|1990|p=43}} The document dated [[Bikram Samvat]] 1833 [[Bhadra]] Vadi 3 Roj 6 (i.e. Friday 2 August 1776), shows that he had carried the title of [[Dewan]] along with Vamsharaj Pande.{{sfn|D.R. Regmi|1975|p=272}} King [[Pratap Singh Shah]] died on 22 November 1777 A.D.{{sfn|Karmacharya|2005|p=36}} leaving his infant son [[Rana Bahadur Shah]] as the [[King of Nepal]].{{sfn|D.R. Regmi|1975|p=285}} [[Sarbajit Rana Magar]] was made a [[Kaji (Nepal)|Kaji]] along with [[Balbhadra Shah]] and [[Vamsharaj Pande]]{{sfn|Shaha|1990|p=46}} while Daljit Shah was chosen as Chief Chautariya.{{sfn|D.R. Regmi|1975|p=285}}{{sfn|Shaha|1990|p=46}} Historian [[Dilli Raman Regmi]] asserts that Sarbajit was chosen as  [[Mulkaji|Chief Kazi]] (equivalent to [[Prime Minister of Nepal]]).{{sfn|D.R. Regmi|1975|p=285}} Historian [[Rishikesh Shah]] asserts that Sarbajit was the head of the Nepalese government for a short period in 1778.{{sfn|Shaha|2001|p=21}} Afterwards, rivalry arose between Prince [[Bahadur Shah of Nepal]] and [[Queen Rajendra of Nepal|Queen Rajendra Laxmi]]. In the rivalry, Sarbajit led the followers of the Queen opposed to Sriharsh Pant who led the followers of Bahadur Shah.<ref name=\"himalaya\">{{cite web|url=http://himalaya.socanth.cam.ac.uk/collections/journals/ancientnepal/pdf/ancient_nepal_121-122_01.pdf |title=Journal |website=himalaya.socanth.cam.ac.uk |format=PDF}}</ref> The group of Bharadars (officers) led by Sarbajit poisoned the ears of Rajendra Laxmi against Bahadur Shah.{{sfn|Rana|1978|p=6}} Rajendra Laxmi succeeded in the confinement of Prince Bahadur Shah with the help of her new minister Sarbajit.{{sfn|Mahesh Chandra Regmi|1975|p=214}} Guru Gajraj Mishra came to rescue Bahadur Shah on the condition that Bahadur Shah should leave the country.{{sfn|Mahesh Chandra Regmi|1975|p=214}}{{sfn|T.U. History Association|1977|p=5}} Also, his rival Sriharsh Pant was branded outcast and expelled instead of execution which was prohibited for [[Brahmin]]s.<ref name=\"himalaya\"/>\n\nPrince Bahadur Shah confined his sister-in-law Queen Rajendra Laxmi on the charge of having illicit relation with Sarbajit{{sfn|Regmi|1975|p=215}} on 31 August 1778.{{sfn|Karmacharya|2005|p=36}}{{sfn|D.R. Regmi|1975|p=294}}{{sfn|Bajracharya|1992|p=21}} Subsequently, Sarbajit was executed inside the palace by Prince Bahadur Shah{{sfn|Mahesh Chandra Regmi|1975|p=215}}{{sfn|Puratattva Bibhag|1990|p=76}} with the help of male servants of the royal palace.{{sfn|Mahesh Chandra Regmi|1975|p=215}} Historian Bhadra Ratna Bajracharya asserts that it was actually Chautariya Daljit Shah who led the opposing group against Sarbajit Rana and Rajendra Laxmi.{{sfn|Bajracharya|1992|pp=21-22}} The letter dated [[Bikram Samvat|B.S.]] 1835 [[Bhadra (Nepali calendar)|Bhadra]] Sudi 11 Roj 4 (1778 A.D.) to Narayan Malla and Vrajabasi Pande asserts the death of Sarbajit under misconduct and the appointment of Bahadur Shah as [[regent]].{{sfn|Karmacharya|2005|p=36}} The death of Sarbajit Rana Magar is considered to have marked the initiation of court conspiracies and massacres in the newly unified Kingdom of Nepal.{{sfn|T.U. History Association|1977|p=5}} Historian [[Baburam Acharya]] points that the sanctions against Queen Rajendra Laxmi under moral misconduct was a mistake of Bahadur Shah. Similarly, the murder of Sarbajit was condemned by many historians as an act of injustice.{{sfn|Bajracharya|1992|p=22}}\n\n[[Vamsharaj Pande]], once Dewan of Nepal and son of the popular commander [[Kalu Pande]], was beheaded on the conspiracy of [[Queen Rajendra of Nepal|Queen Rajendra Laxmi]] with his support.{{sfn|Karmacharya|2005|p=46}}{{sfn|Shaha|2001|p=62}} In the special tribunal meeting at Bhandarkhal garden, east of Kathmandu Durbar, Swaroop Singh held Vamsharaj liable for letting the King of Parbat, Kirtibam Malla to run away in the battle a year ago.{{sfn|Bajracharya|1992|p=35}} He had a fiery conversation with Vamsharaj before Vamsharaj was declared guilty and was subsequently executed by beheading on the tribunal.<ref name=\"himalaya\"/> Historian [[Rishikesh Shah]] and Ganga Karmacharya claim that he was executed on March 1785.{{sfn|Karmacharya|2005|p=46}}{{sfn|Shaha|2001|p=62}} Bhadra Ratna Bajracharya and Tulsi Ram Vaidya claim that he was executed on 21 April 1785.{{sfn|Bajracharya|1992|p=35}}<ref name=\"himalaya\"/> On 2 July 1785, his stiff opponent Prince Regent [[Bahadur Shah of Nepal]] was arrested and on the eleventh day of imprisonment on 13 July, his only supporter Queen Rajendra Laxmi died.{{sfn|Karmacharya|2005|p=46}}{{sfn|Shaha|2001|p=62}} Then onwards, Bahadur Shah took over the regency of his nephew King [[Rana Bahadur Shah]]{{sfn|Pradhan|2012|p=10}} and on the first moments of his regency ordered Swaroop Singh who was in [[Pokhara]] to be beheaded there {{sfn|Bibhag|1990|p=77}}{{sfn|Shaha|2001|p=63}} on the charges of [[treason]].{{sfn|Hamal|1995|p=81}} He had gone to Kaski to join Daljit Shah's military campaign of Kaski fearing retaliation of the old courtiers due to his conspiracy against Vamsharaj. He was executed on 24th [[Shrawan (Nepali calendar)|Shrawan]] 1842 [[Bikram Samvat|B.S]].{{sfn|Bibhag|1990|p=77}}\n\n===Tibetan conflict===\n{{See|Sino-Nepalese War}}\n[[File:Battle of Jhunga.jpg|thumb|Battle of Jhunga in 1788 A.D., Nepali forces (in black) achieved victory against Tibetan forces (in red & yellow)]]\nAfter the death of Prithvi Narayan Shah, the Shah dynasty began to expand their kingdom into what is present day North India. Between 1788 and 1791, Nepal invaded Tibet and robbed [[Tashi Lhunpo Monastery]] of [[Shigatse]]. Tibet sought Chinese help and the [[Qianlong Emperor]] of the Chinese [[Qing Dynasty]] appointed [[Fuk'anggan]] commander-in-chief of the Tibetan campaign. Heavy damages were inflicted on both sides. The Nepali forces retreated step by step back to Nuwakot to stretch Sino-Tibetan forces uncomfortably. Chinese launched uphill attack during the daylight and failed to succeed due to strong counterattack with [[Khukuri]] at Nuwakot.<ref name=\"nepalarmythree\"/> The Chinese army suffered a major setback when they tried to cross a monsoon-flooded Betrawati, close to the Gorkhali palace in Nuwakot.<ref>Stiller, L.F., \"The Rise of the House of Gorkha.\" Patna Jesuit Society. Patna. 1975.</ref> A stalemate ensued when [[Fuk'anggan]] was keen to protect his troops and wanted to negotiate at Nuwakot. The treaty was favouring more to Chinese side where Nepal had to send tributes to the Chinese emperor.<ref name=\"nepalarmythree\"/>\n\n\n==See also==\n* [[History of Nepal]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Fr. Giuseppe. (1799). ''An account of the kingdom of Nepal''. Asiatic Researches. Vol 2. (1799). pp. 307\u2013322.\n* Reed, David. (2002). ''The Rough Guide to Nepal''. DK Publishing, Inc.\n* Wright, Daniel, ''History of Nepal''. New Delhi-Madras, Asian Educational Services, 1990\n\n{{Nepal topics}}\n[[Category:History of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Gurkhas]]\n[[Category:National unifications]]\n", "name_user": "110.44.125.184", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unification_of_Nepal"}
{"title_page": "Democrats for a Strong Bulgaria", "text_new": "{{short description|Bulgarian political party}}\n{{update|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox political party\n|country = Bulgaria\n|colorcode = #1e2a5b\n|name = Democrats for a Strong Bulgaria\n|native_name = \u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438 \u0437\u0430 \u0441\u0438\u043b\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f\n|logo = File:DSB logo 2018.png\n|leader = [[Atanas Atanasov (politician)|Atanas Atanasov]]\n|foundation = 30 May 2004\n|headquarters = 18 Vitosha Blvd.<br />[[Sofia]] 1000\n|seats1_title= [[National Assembly of Bulgaria|National Assembly]]\n|seats1 = {{Composition bar|0|240|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n|seats2_title = [[European Parliament]]:\n|seats2 = {{Composition bar|1|17|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n|ideology = {{nowrap|[[National conservatism]]}}<ref name=\"Bakke\">{{Cite book |first=Elisabeth |last=Bakke |chapter=Party systems since 1989 |title=Central and Southeast European Politics Since 1989 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |year=2010 |page=79 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFXdiS25N78C&pg=PA79 |accessdate=17 November 2011|isbn=9781139487504 }}</ref><br>[[Pro-Europeanism]]<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=7stgCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA639 Routledge Handbook of European Elections edited by Donatella M. Viola, page 639]</ref><br>[[Anti-communism]]\n|position = [[Centre-right]]\n|national= ''None''\n|international = ''None''\n|european = [[European People's Party]]\n|europarl = [[European People's Party (European Parliament group)|EPP Group]]\n|colours = [[Blue]]\n|website = {{url|http://www.dsb.bg/}}\n}}\n'''Democrats for a Strong Bulgaria''' ({{lang-bg|\u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438 \u0437\u0430 \u0441\u0438\u043b\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f}}, ''Demokrati za silna B\u0103lgarija'', \u0414\u0421\u0411, ''DSB'') is a [[list of political parties in Bulgaria|political party]] in [[Bulgaria]] established by former Bulgarian Prime Minister [[Ivan Kostov]] (1997\u20132001). The [[motto]] of the party is \"''For a Strong Bulgaria in Unified Europe''\".\n\n== History ==\nKostov resigned as chairman of the [[United Democratic Forces]] after a painful election defeat in June 2001 to [[Simeon Saxe-Coburg-Gotha]]'s newly established [[National Movement for Stability and Progress|National Movement for Simeon II]]. The UDF had suffered heavily from allegations of corruption and increased unemployment after having carried out economic reforms during its four-year term.\n\nWith time 29 (out of 51) UDF MPs including Kostov grew increasingly dissatisfied with the new UDF leadership of chairwoman [[Nadezhda Mihailova]], who was the foreign minister in Kostov's own government. Following another defeat for the UDF in the 2003 local elections and after Nadezhda Mihailova's refusal to bear the responsibility and resign, the group of 29 around Kostov announced their departure from the UDF and the formation of a new political force, the DSB.\n\nDSB is a member of the [[European People's Party]] (EPP).\n\nOn 30 March 2020, during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bulgaria|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the country]], the Sofia City Council members from Democratic Bulgaria, a coalition Democrats for a Strong Bulgaria is part of, proposed a package of measures in defense of local economy. Those included ten-fold tax cut for landlords for leasing an apartment, rent-free period for businesses renting municipal property for the duration of the national emergency, and reorganization of Sofia public transport in view of the reduced passenger flow.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u0445\u043c\u0435 \u043c\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0438 \u0432 \u043f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0449 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u043e\u0444\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0438\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u043a\u0430 |url=https://sofia.demokrati.bg/document/merki-v-pomosht-na-sofijskata-ikonomika/?fbclid=IwAR0kZzTB7x32He6u3x4BPqdOK3OCPIWBQP3le5c7yYzS1vpYenEuWVfE5ek |website=Demokratichna Bulgaria |language=Bulgarian |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\"\u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f\" \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043b\u0430\u0433\u0430 \u0434\u0435\u0441\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u044a\u0442\u0438 \u043f\u043e-\u043d\u0438\u0441\u044a\u043a \u0434\u0430\u043d\u044a\u043a \u0437\u0430 \u043e\u0442\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0430\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u043d\u0430\u0435\u043c \u0432 \u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u044f |url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/03/30/4048250_demokratichna_bulgariia_predlaga_deset_puti_po-nisuk/ |website=dnevnik.bg |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=Bulgarian |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Leaders ==\n[[Image:DSB logo.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Former DSB logo]]\nIt was chaired by [[Ivan Kostov]] since its establishment in May 2004 until June 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bnt.bg/bg/news/view/103350/radan_kynev_e_novijat_lider_na_dsb |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-11-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730031942/http://bnt.bg/bg/news/view/103350/radan_kynev_e_novijat_lider_na_dsb |archivedate=2013-07-30 }}</ref> Since then it has been chaired by [[Radan Kanev]].\n\n== Electoral results ==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2019}}\n\n=== 25 June 2005 legislative elections ===\nAt the last [[legislative]] [[elections in Bulgaria|elections]], 25 June 2005, DSB won 7.0% of the popular vote and 17 out of 240 seats, their support coming mainly from big cities (appr. 18% of voters in [[Sofia]]). See also [[2005 Bulgarian parliamentary election]]\n\n=== 29 October 2005 partial local elections ===\nThe DSB candidate for Mayor of [[Sofia]], former finance minister and head of the [[Bulgarian National Bank|Central Bank of Bulgaria]] Svetoslav Gavriyski arrived third in the first round with 18% of the votes.\n\nThe last political surveys (March'2006) show the serious decreasing of the people support for the Kostov's party. Less than only 4% of the political support moves today this party to a position behind BSP (socialists), ATAKA (nationalists party), NDSV (Simeon II former king party) and UDF.{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}}\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ [[National Assembly of Bulgaria|Bulgarian Parliament]]\n! Election\n! Seats won\n! Votes\n! %\n! Rank\n! Government\n|-\n! [[2005 Bulgarian parliamentary election|2005]]\n| {{Composition bar|17|240|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 234,788\n| 6.44%\n| 6th\n| {{no|Opposition}}\n|-\n! [[2009 Bulgarian parliamentary election|2009]]\n| {{Composition bar|15|240|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 285,671\n| 6.76%\n| 5th{{efn|name=BC|As part of the [[Blue Coalition]].}}\n| {{no|Opposition}}\n|-\n! [[2013 Bulgarian parliamentary election|2013]]\n| {{Composition bar|0|240|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 103,638\n| 2.93%\n| 7th\n| Extra-parliamentary\n|-\n! [[2014 Bulgarian parliamentary election|2014]]\n| {{Composition bar|23|240|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 291,806\n| 8.89%\n| 4th{{efn|name=RB|As part of the [[Reformist Bloc]].}}\n| {{yes|Coalition government}}\n|-\n! [[2017 Bulgarian parliamentary election|2017]]\n| {{Composition bar|0|240|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 86,984\n| 2.48%\n| 6th{{efn|name=NR|As part of New Republic, a coalition between Bulgarian democratic community, Union for Plovdiv and Democrats for a Strong Bulgaria.}}\n| Extra-parliamentary\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text\" align=\"center\"\n|+ [[President of Bulgaria|Presidential]] elections\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Election year\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Candidate\n!colspan=\"3\"|First round\n!colspan=\"3\"|Second round\n|-\n!Votes\n!%\n!Rank\n!Votes\n!%\n!Rank\n|-\n! [[2016 Bulgarian presidential election|2016]]\n| [[Traycho Traykov]]\n| 224,734\n| 5.87%\n| 6th{{efn|name=RB}}\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ [[European Parliament]]\n! Election\n! Seats won\n! Votes\n! %\n! Rank\n|-\n! [[2007 European Parliament election in Bulgaria|2007]]\n| {{Composition bar|0|18|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 84,350\n| 4.35%\n| 7th\n|-\n! [[2009 European Parliament election in Bulgaria|2009]]\n| {{Composition bar|2|18|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 204,817\n| 7.95%\n| 6th{{efn|name=BC}}\n|-\n! [[2014 European Parliament election in Bulgaria|2014]]\n| {{Composition bar|1|17|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 144,532\n| 6.45%\n| 5th{{efn|name=RB}}\n|-\n! [[2019 European Parliament election in Bulgaria|2019]]\n| {{Composition bar|1|17|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 118,484\n| 6.06%\n| 5th{{efn|name=DB|As part of Democratic Bulgaria, a coalition between [[Yes, Bulgaria!]], [[The Greens (Bulgaria)|The Greens]] and Democrats for a Strong Bulgaria.}}\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n== Program ==\n[[File:DSB 29.11.2008.jpg|thumb|The fifth national meeting of the DSB in [[Sofia]]]]\nThe DSB define themselves as a moderately [[Conservatism|conservative]], but also nationally oriented<ref name=\"Bakke\"/> party.\n\nThey regard themselves as successors of the ruling mandate of the [[United Democratic Forces]] (1997\u20132001) and promise to stand up for its achievements and build on them.\n\nThe party stands for a new structure, composition and organization of the constitutional powers in Bulgaria through the adoption of a new [[Constitution]].\n\nThey propose a decrease in overall taxes, the creation of an [[investor]]-friendly tax and insurance environment and tax and insurance incentives to small and medium-sized enterprises and to companies that generate long-term employment. The DSB propose to reform the law enforcement institutions in order to cut off their connection with the criminal world and in order to abolish corruption. They also insist on making officials of the executive and the other branches of power fully accountable for their actions stripping them of their [[Sovereign immunity|immunity]].\n\nThey support the independence and public nature of the [[universal health care|National Health Insurance Fund]], the promotion of additional health insurance schemes through optional funds and competition between these funds.\n\nThe DSB stand for integration and coexistence of different ethnic communities on the basis of equality before the Law, regardless of religion, gender and origin and strongly oppose [[Ahmed Dogan]], the leader of the [[Movement for Rights and Freedoms]] claiming that his \"[[Bulgarian Ethnic Model]]\" is one of separation and encapsulation of [[Turks in Bulgaria|Bulgarian Turks]], aimed at monopolizing their vote instead of integrating them in Bulgarian society. This opposition has often been wrongly referred to as anti-minority [[nationalism]].\n\nKostov and the DSB are outspoken opponents of the [[Bulgarian Socialist Party]] whom they regard as the heir to the totalitarian [[Bulgarian Communist Party]] and define them as their main political enemy. They have also often criticized ex-Prime Minister [[Simeon Saxe-Coburg-Gotha]] for allying himself with the socialists and who is accused, very much like Kostov was, of corruption.\n\nKostov's government was the one to begin adhesion talks with the [[European Union]] back in 1999 and the DSB continue to support European orientation for the country.\n\nBefore the elections of June 2005 Democrats for a Strong Bulgaria issued the Treaty for a Strong Bulgaria which is a 12-point resume of their program.\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal-inline|Conservatism}}\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.dsb.bg/ Official website]\n*[http://www.dsb-is.net/ Forum]\n{{Bulgarian political parties}}\n{{European People's Party}}\n\n[[Category:2004 establishments in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Conservative parties in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Member parties of the European People's Party]]\n[[Category:National conservative parties]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Pro-European political parties]]\n[[Category:Anti-communist parties]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Bulgarian political party}}\n{{update|date=May 2019}}\n{{Infobox political party\n|country = Bulgaria\n|colorcode = #1e2a5b\n|name = Democrats for a Strong Bulgaria\n|native_name = \u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438 \u0437\u0430 \u0441\u0438\u043b\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f\n|logo = File:DSB logo 2018.png\n|leader = [[Atanas Atanasov (politician)|Atanas Atanasov]]\n|foundation = 30 May 2004\n|headquarters = 18 Vitosha Blvd.<br />[[Sofia]] 1000\n|seats1_title= [[National Assembly of Bulgaria|National Assembly]]\n|seats1 = {{Composition bar|0|240|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n|seats2_title = [[European Parliament]]:\n|seats2 = {{Composition bar|1|17|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n|ideology = {{nowrap|[[National conservatism]]}}<ref name=\"Bakke\">{{Cite book |first=Elisabeth |last=Bakke |chapter=Party systems since 1989 |title=Central and Southeast European Politics Since 1989 |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |year=2010 |page=79 |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oFXdiS25N78C&pg=PA79 |accessdate=17 November 2011|isbn=9781139487504 }}</ref><br>[[Pro-Europeanism]]<ref>[https://books.google.ca/books?id=7stgCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA639 Routledge Handbook of European Elections edited by Donatella M. Viola, page 639]</ref><br>[[Anti-communism]]\n|position = [[Centre-right]]\n|national= ''None''\n|international = ''None''\n|european = [[European People's Party]]\n|europarl = [[European People's Party (European Parliament group)|EPP Group]]\n|colours = [[Blue]]\n|website = {{url|http://www.dsb.bg/}}\n}}\n'''Democrats for a Strong Bulgaria''' ({{lang-bg|\u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438 \u0437\u0430 \u0441\u0438\u043b\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f}}, ''Demokrati za silna B\u0103lgarija'', \u0414\u0421\u0411, ''DSB'') is a [[list of political parties in Bulgaria|political party]] in [[Bulgaria]] established by former Bulgarian Prime Minister [[Ivan Kostov]] (1997\u20132001). The [[motto]] of the party is \"''For a Strong Bulgaria in Unified Europe''\".\n\n== History ==\nKostov resigned as chairman of the [[United Democratic Forces]] after a painful election defeat in June 2001 to [[Simeon Saxe-Coburg-Gotha]]'s newly established [[National Movement for Stability and Progress|National Movement for Simeon II]]. The UDF had suffered heavily from allegations of corruption and increased unemployment after having carried out economic reforms during its four-year term.\n\nWith time 29 (out of 51) UDF MPs including Kostov grew increasingly dissatisfied with the new UDF leadership of chairwoman [[Nadezhda Mihailova]], who was the foreign minister in Kostov's own government. Following another defeat for the UDF in the 2003 local elections and after Nadezhda Mihailova's refusal to bear the responsibility and resign, the group of 29 around Kostov announced their departure from the UDF and the formation of a new political force, the DSB.\n\nDSB is a member of the [[European People's Party]] (EPP).\n\nOn 30 March 2020, during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bulgaria|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the country]], the Sofia City Council members from Democratic Bulgaria, a coalition Democrats for a Strong Bulgaria, proposed a package of measures in defense of local economy. Those included ten-fold tax cut for landlords for leasing an apartment, rent-free period for businesses renting municipal property for the duration of the national emergency, and reorganization of Sofia public transport in view of the reduced passenger flow.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u0445\u043c\u0435 \u043c\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0438 \u0432 \u043f\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0449 \u043d\u0430 \u0441\u043e\u0444\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0438\u043a\u043e\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0438\u043a\u0430 |url=https://sofia.demokrati.bg/document/merki-v-pomosht-na-sofijskata-ikonomika/?fbclid=IwAR0kZzTB7x32He6u3x4BPqdOK3OCPIWBQP3le5c7yYzS1vpYenEuWVfE5ek |website=Demokratichna Bulgaria |language=Bulgarian |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\"\u0414\u0435\u043c\u043e\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0447\u043d\u0430 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u044f\" \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043b\u0430\u0433\u0430 \u0434\u0435\u0441\u0435\u0442 \u043f\u044a\u0442\u0438 \u043f\u043e-\u043d\u0438\u0441\u044a\u043a \u0434\u0430\u043d\u044a\u043a \u0437\u0430 \u043e\u0442\u0434\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0430\u043f\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u043d\u0430\u0435\u043c \u0432 \u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u044f |url=https://www.dnevnik.bg/bulgaria/2020/03/30/4048250_demokratichna_bulgariia_predlaga_deset_puti_po-nisuk/ |website=dnevnik.bg |accessdate=4 April 2020 |language=Bulgarian |date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Leaders ==\n[[Image:DSB logo.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Former DSB logo]]\nIt was chaired by [[Ivan Kostov]] since its establishment in May 2004 until June 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bnt.bg/bg/news/view/103350/radan_kynev_e_novijat_lider_na_dsb |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-11-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130730031942/http://bnt.bg/bg/news/view/103350/radan_kynev_e_novijat_lider_na_dsb |archivedate=2013-07-30 }}</ref> Since then it has been chaired by [[Radan Kanev]].\n\n== Electoral results ==\n{{Expand section|date=March 2019}}\n\n=== 25 June 2005 legislative elections ===\nAt the last [[legislative]] [[elections in Bulgaria|elections]], 25 June 2005, DSB won 7.0% of the popular vote and 17 out of 240 seats, their support coming mainly from big cities (appr. 18% of voters in [[Sofia]]). See also [[2005 Bulgarian parliamentary election]]\n\n=== 29 October 2005 partial local elections ===\nThe DSB candidate for Mayor of [[Sofia]], former finance minister and head of the [[Bulgarian National Bank|Central Bank of Bulgaria]] Svetoslav Gavriyski arrived third in the first round with 18% of the votes.\n\nThe last political surveys (March'2006) show the serious decreasing of the people support for the Kostov's party. Less than only 4% of the political support moves today this party to a position behind BSP (socialists), ATAKA (nationalists party), NDSV (Simeon II former king party) and UDF.{{Citation needed|date=October 2008}}\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ [[National Assembly of Bulgaria|Bulgarian Parliament]]\n! Election\n! Seats won\n! Votes\n! %\n! Rank\n! Government\n|-\n! [[2005 Bulgarian parliamentary election|2005]]\n| {{Composition bar|17|240|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 234,788\n| 6.44%\n| 6th\n| {{no|Opposition}}\n|-\n! [[2009 Bulgarian parliamentary election|2009]]\n| {{Composition bar|15|240|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 285,671\n| 6.76%\n| 5th{{efn|name=BC|As part of the [[Blue Coalition]].}}\n| {{no|Opposition}}\n|-\n! [[2013 Bulgarian parliamentary election|2013]]\n| {{Composition bar|0|240|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 103,638\n| 2.93%\n| 7th\n| Extra-parliamentary\n|-\n! [[2014 Bulgarian parliamentary election|2014]]\n| {{Composition bar|23|240|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 291,806\n| 8.89%\n| 4th{{efn|name=RB|As part of the [[Reformist Bloc]].}}\n| {{yes|Coalition government}}\n|-\n! [[2017 Bulgarian parliamentary election|2017]]\n| {{Composition bar|0|240|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 86,984\n| 2.48%\n| 6th{{efn|name=NR|As part of New Republic, a coalition between Bulgarian democratic community, Union for Plovdiv and Democrats for a Strong Bulgaria.}}\n| Extra-parliamentary\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text\" align=\"center\"\n|+ [[President of Bulgaria|Presidential]] elections\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Election year\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Candidate\n!colspan=\"3\"|First round\n!colspan=\"3\"|Second round\n|-\n!Votes\n!%\n!Rank\n!Votes\n!%\n!Rank\n|-\n! [[2016 Bulgarian presidential election|2016]]\n| [[Traycho Traykov]]\n| 224,734\n| 5.87%\n| 6th{{efn|name=RB}}\n| -\n| -\n| -\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ [[European Parliament]]\n! Election\n! Seats won\n! Votes\n! %\n! Rank\n|-\n! [[2007 European Parliament election in Bulgaria|2007]]\n| {{Composition bar|0|18|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 84,350\n| 4.35%\n| 7th\n|-\n! [[2009 European Parliament election in Bulgaria|2009]]\n| {{Composition bar|2|18|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 204,817\n| 7.95%\n| 6th{{efn|name=BC}}\n|-\n! [[2014 European Parliament election in Bulgaria|2014]]\n| {{Composition bar|1|17|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 144,532\n| 6.45%\n| 5th{{efn|name=RB}}\n|-\n! [[2019 European Parliament election in Bulgaria|2019]]\n| {{Composition bar|1|17|hex=#1e2a5b}}\n| 118,484\n| 6.06%\n| 5th{{efn|name=DB|As part of Democratic Bulgaria, a coalition between [[Yes, Bulgaria!]], [[The Greens (Bulgaria)|The Greens]] and Democrats for a Strong Bulgaria.}}\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n== Program ==\n[[File:DSB 29.11.2008.jpg|thumb|The fifth national meeting of the DSB in [[Sofia]]]]\nThe DSB define themselves as a moderately [[Conservatism|conservative]], but also nationally oriented<ref name=\"Bakke\"/> party.\n\nThey regard themselves as successors of the ruling mandate of the [[United Democratic Forces]] (1997\u20132001) and promise to stand up for its achievements and build on them.\n\nThe party stands for a new structure, composition and organization of the constitutional powers in Bulgaria through the adoption of a new [[Constitution]].\n\nThey propose a decrease in overall taxes, the creation of an [[investor]]-friendly tax and insurance environment and tax and insurance incentives to small and medium-sized enterprises and to companies that generate long-term employment. The DSB propose to reform the law enforcement institutions in order to cut off their connection with the criminal world and in order to abolish corruption. They also insist on making officials of the executive and the other branches of power fully accountable for their actions stripping them of their [[Sovereign immunity|immunity]].\n\nThey support the independence and public nature of the [[universal health care|National Health Insurance Fund]], the promotion of additional health insurance schemes through optional funds and competition between these funds.\n\nThe DSB stand for integration and coexistence of different ethnic communities on the basis of equality before the Law, regardless of religion, gender and origin and strongly oppose [[Ahmed Dogan]], the leader of the [[Movement for Rights and Freedoms]] claiming that his \"[[Bulgarian Ethnic Model]]\" is one of separation and encapsulation of [[Turks in Bulgaria|Bulgarian Turks]], aimed at monopolizing their vote instead of integrating them in Bulgarian society. This opposition has often been wrongly referred to as anti-minority [[nationalism]].\n\nKostov and the DSB are outspoken opponents of the [[Bulgarian Socialist Party]] whom they regard as the heir to the totalitarian [[Bulgarian Communist Party]] and define them as their main political enemy. They have also often criticized ex-Prime Minister [[Simeon Saxe-Coburg-Gotha]] for allying himself with the socialists and who is accused, very much like Kostov was, of corruption.\n\nKostov's government was the one to begin adhesion talks with the [[European Union]] back in 1999 and the DSB continue to support European orientation for the country.\n\nBefore the elections of June 2005 Democrats for a Strong Bulgaria issued the Treaty for a Strong Bulgaria which is a 12-point resume of their program.\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal-inline|Conservatism}}\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://www.dsb.bg/ Official website]\n*[http://www.dsb-is.net/ Forum]\n{{Bulgarian political parties}}\n{{European People's Party}}\n\n[[Category:2004 establishments in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Conservative parties in Bulgaria]]\n[[Category:Member parties of the European People's Party]]\n[[Category:National conservative parties]]\n[[Category:Political parties established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Pro-European political parties]]\n[[Category:Anti-communist parties]]\n", "name_user": "Oksvobomchatka", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Democrats_for_a_Strong_Bulgaria"}
{"title_page": "Charles Matthews (basketball)", "text_new": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name            =  Charles Matthews\n| image           = 20181204 Charles Matthews at UM-NW game (4).jpg\n| image_size      = \n| caption         = Matthews for the [[2018-19 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2018-19 Michigan Wolverines]]\n| position        = [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft       = 6\n| height_in       = 6\n| weight_lb       = 205\n| league          = \n| team            = Free agent\n| number          = \n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1996|11|15}}\n| birth_place     = [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]]\n| nationality     = American\n| high_school     = [[St. Rita of Cascia High School|St. Rita of Cascia]]<br>(Chicago, Illinois)\n| college         =\n* [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky]] (2015\u20132016)\n* [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan]] (2017\u20132019)\n| draft_year      = 2019\n| career_start    = \n| years1          = \n| team1           = \n| highlights      =\n* [[Jordan Brand Classic]] (2015)\n* [[USA Basketball]] 3\u00d73 Tournament MVP (2014)\n}}\n'''Charles I. Matthews''' (born November 15, 1996) is an American [[basketball]] player. He played college basketball for the [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan Wolverines]]. He played his freshman season for the [[2015\u201316 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team]] after attending [[St. Rita of Cascia High School]]. As a high school senior he was a 2015 [[Jordan Brand Classic]] All-American selection. He earned West Region Most Outstanding Player in the [[2018 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2018 NCAA Basketball Tournament]] for the [[2017\u201318 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2017\u201318 team]] that won the [[2018 Big Ten Conference Men's Basketball Tournament]] and reached the [[2018 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Championship Game|2018 NCAA Championship Game]]. After playing his [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] junior season for the [[2018\u201319 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2018\u201319 Wolverines]], he declared for the [[2019 NBA Draft]].\n\n==Early life==\nMatthews was raised in the [[Avalon Park, Chicago|Avalon Park]]  [[Community areas of Chicago|Community area of Chicago]],<ref name=KtCMwgtbnMbs/> near 79th Street and Cottage Grove Avenue,<ref name=SRCMDSBBPotY/> which is on the borderline between the [[Chatham, Chicago|Chatham]] and [[Greater Grand Crossing, Chicago|Greater Grand Crossing]] Community areas on the [[South Side, Chicago|South Side]].<ref name=SRCMDSBBPotY/> Matthews briefly lived in [[Matteson, Illinois]] before returning to the South Side where he attended Ray Elementary and began his basketball career at the 63rd and Stony Island [[YMCA]].<ref name=KtCMwgtbnMbs/> In his youth, he played chess, hockey,<ref name=KtCMwgtbnMbs/> the [[trombone]] and [[skateboard]]ed, but he began to take basketball seriously the summer before his high school freshman year.<ref name=SRCMDSBBPotY/> Matthews committed to playing basketball for [[John Calipari]] and the [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky Wildcats]] on February 26, 2014 during his junior year. At the time, he was rated as the number 11 player and number 3 [[shooting guard]] in the national class of 2015 by [[Rivals.com]] and number 12 player by [[ESPN]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailyillini.com/uncategorized/2014/02/25/five-star-shooting-guard-charles-matthews-to-make-decision-wednesday/|title=Five-star shooting guard Charles Matthews to make decision Wednesday|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=February 25, 2014|work=[[The Daily Illini]]|author=Hettinger, Johnathan}}</ref><ref name=KL2FSCM>{{cite web|url=http://www.slamonline.com/college-hs/college/kentucky-lands-2015-five-star-sg-charles-matthews/#KlZULdXsBVIwx7Fz.97|title=Kentucky Lands 2015 Five-Star SG Charles Matthews|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=February 26, 2014|work=[[SLAM Magazine]]}}</ref> Among his other offers at the time were [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball|Illinois]], [[Kansas Jayhawks men's basketball|Kansas]], [[Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball|Marquette]] and [[Michigan State Spartans men's basketball|Michigan State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2016/06/report_kentucky_transfer_charl.html|title=Report: Kentucky transfer Charles Matthews, a former top-100 recruit, considering Michigan|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=June 1, 2016|publisher=[[MLive.com]]|author=Quinn, Brendan F.}}</ref> Matthews was the first to commit to playing basketball for Kentucky's 2015 class.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/comprehensive-breakdown-charles-matthews-commits-to-kentucky/|title=Comprehensive breakdown: Charles Matthews commits to Kentucky|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=February 26, 2014|work=[[CBS Sports]]|author=Borzello, Jeff}}</ref> On June 1, Matthews won the 2014 [[USA Basketball]] 3&ndash;on&ndash;3 Under-18 National Championship Tournament with teammates Braxton Blackwell, Tim Delaney and Kipper Nichols. Matthew earned the tournament's Most Valuable Player (MVP) award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usab.com/news-events/news/2014/06/us-youth-olympic-womens-basketball-team-named-after-completion-of-3x3-u18-national-championship.aspx|title=U.S. Youth Olympic Women's Team Named After 3x3 U18 National Championship Ends|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=June 1, 2014|publisher=[[USA Basketball]]}}</ref>\n\nMatthews officially signed his [[National Letter of Intent]] on National Signing Day, November 22, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/signing-day-chicago-area-basketball-signees/|title=Signing Day: Chicago-area basketball signees|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=November 22, 2014|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=}}</ref> During Matthews' four-year high school career at St. Rita's, he led the team to 82 wins and four straight Chicago Catholic League South championships, including a 26&ndash;4 record as a senior.<ref name=SRCMDSBBPotY>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/daily-southtown/sports/ct-sta-boys-basketball-player-of-year-charles-matthews-st-0328-20150327-story.html|title=St. Rita's Charles Matthews, Daily Southtown Boys Basketball Player of the Year|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=March 27, 2015|work=[[Daily Southtown]]|author=Disabato, Pat}}</ref> As a junior, he averaged 17.0 [[point (basketball)|points]] and 5.0 [[rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] for the 21&ndash;8 St. Rita's team that was eliminated from the 2014 [[Illinois High School Association|IHSA]] Class 4A playoffs by the [[Jahlil Okafor]]-led [[Whitney M. Young Magnet High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-03-14/sports/chi-jahlil-okafor-whitney-young-sectional-final-03-20140314_1_jahlil-okafor-charles-matthews-dominique-matthews|title=Jahlil Okafor, Young too much for St. Rita|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=March 14, 2014|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Helfgot, Mike}}</ref><ref name=UofMBio/> As a senior, Matthews averaged 21.3 points and 6.2 rebounds and a 47 [[field goal percentage]].<ref name=SRCMDSBBPotY/><ref name=MAMWtR/> After his senior season, he was a selection for the [[Associated Press]]' Class-4A All-State first team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pjstar.com/article/20150319/SPORTS/150318927|title=Lots of stars, fewer spots on 3A/4A all-state teams|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=March 19, 2015|work=[[Peoria Journal Star]]}}</ref> Matthews' national ranking fell significantly from the time he committed to Kentucky to the end of his high school career.<ref>{{cite web|last=Roberts|first=Ben|url=http://www.kentucky.com/sports/college/kentucky-sports/uk-recruiting/article44594571.html|title=Though his stock has declined, skills of UK signee Matthews haven't, high school coach says|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=April 16, 2015|website=[[Kentucky.com]]}}</ref> Although his final rankings were 42nd by [[ESPN]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/basketball/recruiting/player/_/id/144466/charles-matthews|title=Charles Matthews|accessdate=September 19, 2016|website=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> and 48th by [[Rivals.com]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://n.rivals.com/content/prospects/3893|title=Charles Matthews|accessdate=September 19, 2016|website=Rivals.com}}</ref> he graduated as the 59th ranked player according to 247Sports.com's composite ranking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/Season/2015-Basketball/CompositeRecruitRankings?InstitutionGroup=HighSchool|title=2015 Top Basketball Recruits|accessdate=September 19, 2016|website=247Sports.com}}</ref>  Nonetheless, Matthews was selected to play in the 2015 [[Jordan Brand Classic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jordanbrandclassic.com/2015-all-american-boys-team-bios/|title=2015 All-American Boys Team Bios|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=|publisher=[[Jordan Brand Classic]]}}</ref> At Kentucky, he joined fellow Chicagoan and former [[Amateur Athletic Union|AAU]] teammate [[Tyler Ulis]] in the Kentucky backcourt.<ref name=KL2FSCM/>\n\n==College career==\n===Kentucky===\n[[File:Charles-Matthews.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Matthews with the [[2015\u201316 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team|2015\u201316 Wildcats]]]]\nMatthews played in 36 games (including 3 starting assignments) for the 2015\u201316 Kentucky Wildcats, posting averages of 1.7 points, 1.6 rebounds and 10.3 minutes.<ref name=SRgCMrtfKb/> Matthews' three starts included the season opener against [[2015\u201316 Albany Great Danes men's basketball team|Albany]] and the December 26 [[Kentucky\u2013Louisville rivalry|rivalry game]] against #16 ranked [[2015\u201316 Louisville Cardinals men's basketball team|Louisville]],<ref name=UofMBio/> when [[Isaiah Briscoe]] injured his ankle in pregame warmups and sat out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/ncb/recap/_/gameId/400814249|title=Tyler Ulis scores 21 as Kentucky holds off rival Louisville|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=December 26, 2015|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> His season highs were 11 points against [[2015\u201316 South Florida Bulls men's basketball team|South Florida]] (November 27),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/ncb/recap/_/gameId/400809389|title=Murray scores 21, No. 1 Kentucky rolls past USF 84-63|accessdate=March 20, 2018|date=November 27, 2015|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> 7 rebounds against [[2015\u201316 Boston University Terriers men's basketball team|Boston University]] (November 24) and 34 minutes against [[2015\u201316 Illinois State Redbirds men's basketball team|Illinois State]] (November 30).<ref name=UofMBio/>\n\n===Michigan===\n[[File:20180206 UM-NW Charles Matthews 7DM27229.jpg|thumb|Matthews with the [[2017\u201318 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2017\u201318 Wolverines]]]]\nFollowing the season he had a medical procedure on his hip. Matthews was granted his release from the team on May 18, 2016.<ref name=SRgCMrtfKb>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-st-rita-charles-matthews-transfer-kentucky-20160518-story.html|title=St. Rita grad Charles Matthews requests transfer from Kentucky basketball|accessdate=September 16, 2016|date=May 18, 2016|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>  On June 20, 2016, reports confirmed that Matthews, who would have to sit out the 2016\u201317 season, had visited both [[Xavier Musketeers men's basketball|Xavier]] and Michigan and selected Michigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collegebasketball.nbcsports.com/2016/06/20/report-michigan-lands-former-kentucky-guard-matthews/|title=Michigan lands former Kentucky guard Matthews|author=Johnson, Raphielle|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|accessdate=June 21, 2016|date=June 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/16378757/charles-matthews-transferring-kentucky-wildcats-michigan-wolverines|title=Charles Matthews picks Michigan as transfer spot, source says|author=Goodman, Jeff|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=June 21, 2016|date=June 20, 2016}}</ref> Michigan confirmed the story on July 1.<ref name=MAMWtR>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/070116aaa.html|title=Michigan Adds Matthews, Wright-Jones to Roster|accessdate=July 13, 2016|date=July 1, 2016|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> He served on the scout team for the [[2016\u201317 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2016\u201317 Michigan Wolverines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.michigandaily.com/section/mens-basketball/michigan%E2%80%99s-scout-team-gets-creative-simulating-oklahoma-state|title=Michigan\u2019s scout team gets creative simulating for Oklahoma State|accessdate=March 24, 2017|date=March 16, 2017|work=[[Michigan Daily]]|author=Carney, Brandon}}</ref>\n\n====Sophomore Year====\nAs a redshirt sophomore, Matthews scored 20 points against [[2017\u201318 North Florida Ospreys men's basketball team|North Florida]] in his first game at Michigan on November 11, 2017. In the game, he and [[Duncan Robinson (basketball)|Duncan Robinson]] became the first Michigan teammates to score 20 points in a game since March 3, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400986333|title=Michigan pulls away late for 86-66 win over North Florida|accessdate=November 12, 2017|date=November 11, 2017|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/news/2017/11/11/mens-basketball-wolverines-use-second-half-burst-to-down-north-florida-in-2017-18-opener.aspx|title=Wolverines Use Second-Half Burst to Down North Florida in 2017-18 Opener|accessdate=November 12, 2017|date=November 11, 2017|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> Matthews posted career-highs of 28 points and eight rebounds in the first-round game of the [[2017 Maui Invitational Tournament]] against [[2017\u201318 LSU Tigers basketball team|LSU]] on November 20  but only made one of two free throws with Michigan trailing by two points with 9 seconds remaining.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400986374|title=LSU rallies late for 77-75 win over Michigan in Maui|accessdate=November 21, 2017|date=November 21, 2017|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/news/2017/11/21/mens-basketball-wolverines-rally-against-lsu-falls-just-short-in-maui-opener.aspx|title=Wolverines' Rally Against LSU Falls Just Short in Maui Opener|accessdate=November 21, 2017|date=November 21, 2017|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> The following night, he posted his first career [[double-double]] with 22 points (on 8-of-8 [[field goal (basketball)|field goal]] shooting) and 10 rebounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401000094|title=Michigan rolls over Chaminade 102-64 at Maui Invitational|accessdate=November 22, 2017|date=November 21, 2017|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/news/2017/11/21/mens-basketball-michigan-rolls-past-chaminade-at-maui-invitational.aspx|title=Michigan Rolls Past Chaminade at Maui Invitational|accessdate=November 22, 2017|date=November 21, 2017|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> On November 26, Matthews posted a points-[[assist (basketball)|assists]] double-double with 17 points and a career-high 12 assists against [[2017\u201318 UC Riverside Highlanders men's basketball team|UC Riverside]]. Since [[Moe Wagner]] added 21 points and 10 rebounds, the team had its first pair of double-doubles in a game since [[Glenn Robinson III]] and [[Trey Burke]] did so for the [[2012\u201313 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2012\u201313 National Runner-up Wolverines]] on January 6, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400986393|title=Wagner's double-double leads Michigan past UC Riverside,|accessdate=November 27, 2017|date=November 26, 2017|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/news/2017/11/26/mens-basketball-wolverines-dominate-uc-riverside-in-wire-to-wire-win.aspx|title=Wolverines Dominate UC Riverside in Wire-to-Wire Win|accessdate=November 27, 2017|date=November 26, 2017|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> On December 21, Michigan defeated the previously winless [[2017\u201318 Alabama A&M Bulldogs basketball team|Alabama A&M Bulldogs]] 97&ndash;47 as Matthews posted 31 points, another career high.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=400986453|title=Matthews leads Michigan past winless Alabama A&M, 97-47|accessdate=December 22, 2017|date=December 21, 2017|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/news/2017/12/21/mens-basketball-matthews-career-day-propels-u-m-past-alabama-am.aspx|title=Matthews' Career Day Propels U-M Past Alabama A&M|accessdate=December 22, 2017|date=December 21, 2017|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> Matthews tallied 20 or more points six different times before the final four, but none in [[2017\u201318 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season|2017\u201318 Big Ten Conference play]], where he never scored more than 16 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/more/la-sp-ncaa-west-sidebar-20180324-story.html|title=Charles Matthews steps up for the Wolverines in regional final|accessdate=March 27, 2018|date=March 24, 2018|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Fenno, Nathan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2018/03/john_calipari_has_high_praise.html|title=John Calipari has high praise for Charles Matthews after West Region honor|accessdate=March 27, 2018|date=March 26, 2018|website=[[MLive.com]]|author=Slagter, Josh}}</ref>\n\nMatthews averaged 10 points and 5.5 rebounds during Michigan's four games in the [[2018 Big Ten Conference Men's Basketball Tournament]],<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305061946/http://www.bigten.org/library/stats/mbb-tournament.pdf|url=http://www.bigten.org/library/stats/mbb-tournament.pdf|title=2018 Big Ten Men's Basketball Tournament Statistics|accessdate=March 5, 2018|archivedate=March 5, 2018|date=March 4, 2018|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=BigTen.org}}</ref> helping the team win its second consecutive Big Ten  Tournament Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401020042|title=Michigan beats Purdue to win 2nd straight Big Ten Tournament|accessdate=March 4, 2018|date=March 4, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgoblue.com/news/2018/3/4/mens-basketball-back-to-back-wagner-teske-power-michigan-to-second-straight-b1g-tournament-title.aspx|title=Back-to-Back: Wagner, Teske Power Michigan to Second Straight B1G Tournament Title|accessdate=March 4, 2018|date=March 4, 2018|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> On March 15, Michigan began play in the [[2018 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2018 NCAA Tournament]] with a  61&ndash;47 victory over [[2017\u201318 Montana Grizzlies basketball team|Montana]] in the first round, as Matthews posted 20 points and a career-tying 11 rebounds, for his fourth double-double of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401025838|title=Michigan plods to 61-47 win over Montana in NCAA first round|accessdate=March 16, 2018|date=March 16, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgoblue.com/news/2018/3/16/mens-basketball-michigan-eases-into-ncaa-second-round-with-win-over-montana.aspx|title=Michigan Eases into NCAA First Round with Win Over Montana|accessdate=March 16, 2018|date=March 16, 2018|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> On March 21, Matthews became an Academic All-Big Ten honoree.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgoblue.com/news/2018/3/21/general-winter-academic-all-big-ten-selections-announced.aspx|title=Winter Academic All-Big Ten Selections Announced|accessdate=March 29, 2018|date=March 21, 2018|website=MGoBlue.com|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|author=Blevins, Ben}}</ref> On March 24, Michigan defeated [[2017\u201318 Florida State Seminoles men's basketball team|Florida State]] 58&ndash;54 in the West regional finals. Michigan, who established a single-season school record  32 wins with the win, was led by Matthews with 17 points. Matthews, who averaged 16.5 points and 7.3 rebounds to lead Michigan in the first four games of the NCAA tournament, was named West Region Most Outstanding player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgoblue.com/news/2018/3/26/mens-basketball-two-streaks-collide-wolverines-to-face-ramblers-in-ncaa-semifinal.aspx|title=Two Streaks Collide: Wolverines to Face Ramblers in NCAA Semifinal|accessdate=March 29, 2018|date=March 26, 2018|website=MGoBlue.com|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401025885|title=Oh Blue!: Michigan nips Florida St 58-54 to reach Final Four|accessdate=March 25, 2018|date=March 24, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgoblue.com/news/2018/3/24/mens-basketball-hello-final-four-michigans-defense-reigns-against-florida-state.aspx|title=Hello, Final Four! Michigan's Defense Reigns Against Florida State|accessdate=March 25, 2018|date=March 24, 2018|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> On March 31 in the national semifinals, Matthews contributed 17 as Michigan defeated [[2017\u201318 Loyola Ramblers men's basketball team|Loyola\u2013Chicago]] 69&ndash;57.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401025887|title=Wagner, Michigan end Loyola's run 69-57 in Final Four|accessdate=March 31, 2018|date=March 31, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgoblue.com/news/2018/3/31/mens-basketball-wolverines-take-down-loyola-chicago-to-advance-to-ncaa-championship-game.aspx|title=Wolverines Take Down Loyola Chicago to Advance to NCAA Championship Game|accessdate=March 31, 2018|date=March 31, 2018|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/04/01/larry-bird-hakeem-olajuwon-would-know-how-good-moe-wagner-was/|title=Larry Bird, Hakeem Olajuwon would know how good Moe Wagner was|accessdate=April 1, 2018|date=April 1, 2018|work=[[New York Post]]|first=Howie|last=Kussoy}}</ref> The team lost in the [[2018 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Championship Game]] to (#2 Coaches Poll/#2 AP Poll)  [[2017\u201318 Villanova Wildcats men's basketball team|Villanova]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401025888|title=Villanova takes title, 79-62 over Michigan behind DiVincenzo|accessdate=April 3, 2018|date=April 3, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgoblue.com/news/2018/4/2/mens-basketball-michigan-comes-up-short-against-villanova-in-national-championship-game.aspx|title=Michigan Comes Up Short Against Villanova in National Championship Game|accessdate=April 3, 2018|date=April 2, 2018|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> For the tournament he averaged 14.8 points, 6.2 rebounds, 1.2 assists, and 1.2 steals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2767906-march-madness-2018-the-all-tournament-team-after-the-national-championship|title=March Madness 2018: The All-Tournament Team After the National Championship|accessdate=April 5, 2018|date=April 3, 2018|publisher=[[Bleacher Report]]|author=Miller, Kerry}}</ref> For the season, he averaged 13.0 points and 5.5 rebounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/sports/college/university-michigan/2018/04/03/moritz-wagner-charles-matthews-have-decisions-make-nba-draft/33501655/|title=Moritz Wagner, Charles Matthews have decisions to make about NBA Draft|accessdate=April 5, 2018|date=April 3, 2018|work=[[Detroit News]]|author=Hawkins, James}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the season he declared for the [[2018 NBA draft]] without hiring an agent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/23262732/charles-matthews-michigan-wolverwines-entering-draft-agent|title=Michigan's Charles Matthews to test NBA draft waters|accessdate=April 20, 2018|date=April 20, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Borzello, Jeff}}</ref> He didn't received an invitation to the [[NBA Draft combine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/sports/college/university-michigan/2018/05/01/report-matthews-wagner-invited-nba-combine/34439667/|title=Report: Matthews, Wagner invited to NBA Combine|accessdate=May 3, 2018|date=May 1, 2018|work=[[Detroit News]]|author=Hawkins, James}}</ref> Nonetheless, he had workouts with multiple NBA teams.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/nuggets/story/matthews-harris-chat-052218|title=Michigan's Charles Matthews In For Pre-Draft Workout, Chats With Gary Harris|accessdate=May 30, 2018|date=May 22, 2018|publisher=[[NBA.com]]|author=Dempsey, Christopher}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailyknicks.com/2018/05/28/new-york-knicks-host-charles-matthews-pre-draft-workout/|title=New York Knicks host Charles Matthews for pre-draft workout|accessdate=May 30, 2018|date=May 29, 2018|publisher=[[Fansided]]|website=Dailyknicks.com|author=Ogden, Maxwell}}</ref> In the 2017 draft class, 84 of the 137 underclassmen that declared were not invited to the NBA draft combine and only 4 remained in the draft. None of the four was drafted in the [[2017 NBA draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2018/05/with_decision_deadline_looming.html|title=With deadline looming, no word yet if Charles Matthews will pick NBA or Michigan|accessdate=May 30, 2018|date=May 23, 2018|work=[[MLive.com]]|author=Kahn, Andrew}}</ref> Matthews withdrew from the 2018 NBA draft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/ncaa-basketball/news/nba-draft-2018-charles-matthews-withdraws-name-returns-to-michigan/an32eeeyetii1ac65rzjsrm58|title=NBA Draft 2018: Charles Matthews withdraws name, returns to Michigan|accessdate=May 31, 2018|date=May 30, 2018|work=[[Sporting News]]|author=Brzezinski, Alec}}</ref>\n\n====Junior year====\n[[File:20181204 Charles Matthews at UM-NW game (11).jpg|thumb|left|Matthews for the [[2018\u201319 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2018\u201319 Wolverines]]]]\nMatthews was a preseason All-Big Ten selection by the Big Ten Media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bigten.org/news/2018/10/11/big-ten-mens-basketball-basketball-preseason-honors-announced.aspx?path=mbball|title=Big Ten Men\u2019s Basketball Basketball Preseason Honors Announced|accessdate=October 15, 2018|date=October 11, 2018|website=BigTen.org|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> Prior to the season he was one of nine Big Ten players named to the preseason [[John R. Wooden Award]] watchlist and one of eight named to the preseason [[Naismith College Player of the Year]] watchlist.<ref name=WApt5a>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/page/woodenwatch110618/college-basketball-2018-wooden-watch-list-announced|title=Wooden Award preseason top 50 announced|accessdate=November 7, 2018|date=November 6, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://naismithtrophy.com/citizen-naismith-trophy-mens-watch-list-released/|title=Citizen Naismith Trophy Men\u2019s Watch List Released {{!}} Citizen Naismith Trophy|website=naismithtrophy.com|language=en-US|access-date=November 9, 2018}}</ref> On December 15, Michigan defeated [[2018\u201319 Western Michigan Broncos men's basketball team|Western Michigan]] 70&ndash;62 with 25 points and 10 rebounds from Matthews, for his fifth career double-double and first of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082455|title=No. 5 Michigan beats Western Michigan 70-62, stays unbeaten|accessdate=December 15, 2018|date=December 15, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2018/12/15/mens-basketball-matthews-double-double-lifts-wolverines-to-win-over-upstart-wmu.aspx|title=Matthews' Double-Double Lifts Wolverines to Win Over Upstart WMU|accessdate=December 15, 2018|date=December 15, 2018|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref>  On January 13, Michigan defeated [[2018\u201319 Northwestern Wildcats men's basketball team|Northwestern]] to establish a school record for best start at 17&ndash;0 and tied the school's record 17-game win streak.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082459|title=No. 2 Michigan now 17-0 after 80-60 win over Northwestern|accessdate=January 14, 2019|date=January 13, 2019|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/1/13/mens-basketball-career-nights-from-simpson-teske-spark-u-m-to-victory-program-best-17-0-start.aspx|title=Career Nights from Simpson, Teske Spark U-M to Victory, Program-Best 17-0 Start|accessdate=January 14, 2019|date=January 13, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> On January 22, Michigan defeated [[2018\u201319 Minnesota Golden Gophers men's basketball team|Minnesota]] 59&ndash;57 after a [[buzzer beater]] by Matthews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082461|title=Matthews beats buzzer, No. 5 Michigan edges Minnesota 59-57|accessdate=January 22, 2019|date=January 22, 2019|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/1/22/mens-basketball-matthews-buzzer-beater-puts-emphatic-end-to-minnesotas-upset-bid.aspx|title=Matthews' Buzzer Beater Puts Emphatic End to Minnesota's Upset Bid|accessdate=January 22, 2019|date=January 22, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> On January 25, Matthews posted 10 points and a career-tying 11 rebounds for his sixth career double-double in a 69\u201346 victory over Indiana.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082380|title=No. 5 Michigan keeps rolling with 69-46 win at Indiana|accessdate=January 25, 2019|date=January 25, 2019|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/1/25/mens-basketball-wolverines-jump-out-to-big-early-lead-roll-to-victory-over-hoosiers.aspx|title=Wolverines Jump Out to Big Early Lead, Roll to Victory Over Hoosiers|accessdate=January 25, 2019|date=January 25, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> The 23-point victory marked the largest ever by Michigan on the road against Indiana.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/1/28/2018-19-michigan-mens-basketball-awards-and-honors.aspx?path=mbball|title=Awards & Honors: Brazdeikis Tabbed B1G Freshman of the Week|accessdate=January 28, 2019|date=January 28, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129064213/https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/1/28/2018-19-michigan-mens-basketball-awards-and-honors.aspx?path=mbball|archive-date=January 29, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> On February 6, Matthews was the only Big Ten Athlete named a [[Julius Erving Award]] Top 10 finalist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hoophall.com/news/naismith-memorial-basketball-hall-of-fame-narrows-watch-list-for-2019-julius-erving-award|title=Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame Narrows Watch List for 2019 Julius Erving Award|accessdate=February 6, 2019|date=February 6, 2019|publisher=[[Naismith Basketball Hall of Fame]]}}</ref>  On February 9, Michigan defeated (#19/#19) [[2018\u201319 Wisconsin Badgers men's basketball team|Wisconsin]] 61&ndash;52. Michigan was led by Matthews with a game-high 18 points. The teams each scored 27 in the first half and 16 of Matthews 18 came in the second half, including 14 of Michigan's 19 points in a decisive stretch taking the score from 38&ndash;35 to 57&ndash;50 with 23.8 seconds remaining.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082464|title=No. 7 Michigan outlasts No. 19 Wisconsin 61-52|accessdate=February 9, 2019|date=February 9, 2019|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/2/9/mens-basketball-matthews-second-half-scoring-outburst-lifts-u-m-past-no-19-wisconsin.aspx|title=Matthews' Second-Half Scoring Outburst Lifts U-M Past No. 19 Wisconsin|accessdate=February 9, 2019|date=February 9, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> Matthews missed the final three games of the regular season due to an ankle injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/3/9/mens-basketball-michigan-falls-to-michigan-state-in-regular-season-finale.aspx|title=Michigan Falls to Michigan State in Regular-Season Finale|accessdate=March 12, 2019|date=March 9, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> Following the season, he was a [[2018\u201319 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season|2019]] All-[[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]] honorable mention selection (media).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bigten.org/news/2019/3/11/big-ten-unveils-mens-basketball-postseason-honors-on-btn.aspx|title=Big Ten Unveils Men\u2019s Basketball Postseason Honors on BTN|accessdate=March 11, 2019|date=March 11, 2019|website=BigTen.org|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/3/11/mens-basketball-brazdeikis-top-big-ten-freshman-joins-simpson-as-all-b1g-second-teamers.aspx|title=Brazdeikis Top Big Ten Freshman, Joins Simpson on All-B1G Second Team|accessdate=March 11, 2019|date=March 11, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> On March 21, Matthews posted a game-high 22 points and ten rebounds for his seventh career double-double in a 74&ndash;55 victory over [[2018\u201319 Montana Grizzlies basketball team|Montana]] in the first round of the [[2019 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2019 NCAA Tournament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401123405|title=Matthews' double-double leads Michigan past Grizzlies, 74-53|accessdate=March 22, 2019|date=March 22, 2019|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/3/21/mens-basketball-michigan-marches-on-after-rolling-past-montana-in-ncaa-tournament.aspx|title=Michigan Marches on After Rolling Past Montana in NCAA Tournament|accessdate=March 22, 2019|date=March 22, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wywrot, Tom}}</ref> Following the season, on April 9, 2019, Matthews (along with teammates [[Iggy Brazdeikis]] and [[Jordan Poole]]) declared for the [[2019 NBA draft]] with the intention of hiring agents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/4/9/mens-basketball-matthews-poole-and-brazdeikis-to-declare-for-early-entry-into-nba-draft.aspx|title=Matthews, Poole and Brazdeikis to Declare for Early Entry into NBA Draft|accessdate=April 9, 2019|date=April 9, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wywrot, Tom}}</ref> On April 17, Matthews announced, via the Michigan basketball [[Twitter]] account, that he would forgo his remaining year of eligibility at Michigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/sports/college/university-michigan/2019/04/17/michigan-wolverines-charles-matthews-tostay-nba-draft/3498776002/|title=Michigan's Charles Matthews to forgo final season, stay in NBA draft|accessdate=April 18, 2019|date=April 17, 2019|work=[[Detroit News]]|author=Hawkins, James}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nbc25news.com/sports/college/charles-matthews-officially-departs-michigan-for-nba|title=Charles Matthews officially departs Michigan for NBA|accessdate=April 18, 2019|date=April 17, 2019|work=[[WEYI-TV]]|author=Trotman, Jeanna}}</ref>\n\nOn June 9, 2019, Matthews tore his anterior cruciate ligament during a predraft workout with the Boston Celtics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/nba-draft-prospect-charles-matthews-tears-acl-during-celtics-workout-no-timetable-set-for-his-return/|title=NBA Draft prospect Charles Matthews tears ACL during Celtics workout; no timetable set for his return|accessdate=June 24, 2019|date=June 10, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]|author=Siddiqi, DJ}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMatthews' parents are Nichole and Charles Matthews who met at [[Southern Illinois University]].<ref name=UofMBio>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/charles_matthews_1018904.html|title=Charles Matthews 1|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=|website=MGoBlue.com|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> His older brother, Dominique, was a St. Rita's teammate until he graduated in 2014.<ref name=SRCMDSBBPotY/> Dominique went on to play for the [[UIC Flames men's basketball|UIC Flames]].<ref name=UofMBio/> His younger brother, Jordan, was four classes behind Charles at St. Rita's.<ref name=KtCMwgtbnMbs>{{cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/sports/college/university-michigan/wolverines/2017/05/28/michigan-wolverines-basketball-charles-matthews/326067001/|title=How Kentucky transfer Charles Matthews was groomed to be next Michigan basketball star|accessdate=February 7, 2018|date=May 27, 2017 |work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|author=Snyder, Mark}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|style=\"background:#CFECEC; width:1em\"|*\n|Led NCAA Division I\n|}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2015\u201316 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2015\u201316]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2015\u201316 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team|Kentucky]]\n| 36 || 3 || 10.3 || .442 || .250 || .412 || 1.6 || .4 || .4 || .2 || 1.7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2017\u201318]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|Michigan]]\n| style=\"background:#cfecec;\"| '''41'''* || style=\"background:#cfecec;\"| '''41'''* || 30.1 || '''.495''' || '''.318''' || .558 || '''5.5''' || '''2.4''' || .7 || '''.6''' || '''13.0'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2018\u201319]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|Michigan]]\n| 34 || 34 || '''31.5''' || .431 || .299 || '''.645''' || 5.0 || 1.4 || '''1.1''' || .5 || 12.2\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| Career\n| 111 || 78 || 24.1 || .464 || .308 || .576 || 4.1 || 1.4 || .7 || .4 || 9.1\n{{S-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160919154647/http://www.ukathletics.com/sport/m-baskbl/2015/roster/55c227d3e4b073340d388d5e Matthews] @ UKAthletics.com\n* [https://mgoblue.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=18375 Matthews] @ MGoBlue.com\n* [http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/player/_/id/3936297/charles-matthews Stats] at [[ESPN]]\n* [https://www.cbssports.com/collegebasketball/players/playerpage/2202750/charles-matthews Stats] at [[CBS Sports]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Matthews, Charles}}\n[[Category:1996 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 2018 NCAA Men's Division I Final Four]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Illinois]]\n[[Category:Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Michigan Wolverines men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Shooting guards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Chicago]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| name            =  Charles Matthews\n| image           = 20181204 Charles Matthews at UM-NW game (4).jpg\n| image_size      = \n| caption         = Matthews for the [[2018-19 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2018-19 Michigan Wolverines]]\n| position        = [[Shooting guard]]\n| height_ft       = 6\n| height_in       = 6\n| weight_lb       = 205\n| league          = \n| team            = Free agent\n| number          = \n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1996|11|15}}\n| birth_place     = [[Chicago|Chicago, Illinois]]\n| nationality     = American\n| high_school     = [[St. Rita of Cascia High School|St. Rita of Cascia]]<br>(Chicago, Illinois)\n| college         =\n* [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky]] (2015\u20132016)\n* [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan]] (2017\u20132019)\n| draft_year      = 2019\n| career_start    = \n| years1          = \n| team1           = \n| highlights      =\n* [[Jordan Brand Classic]] (2015)\n* [[USA Basketball]] 3\u00d73 Tournament MVP (2014)\n}}\n'''Charles I. Matthews''' (born November 15, 1996) is an American [[basketball]] player. He played college basketball for the [[Michigan Wolverines men's basketball|Michigan Wolverines]]. He played his freshman season for the [[2015\u201316 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team]] after attending [[St. Rita of Cascia High School]]. As a high school senior he was a 2015 [[Jordan Brand Classic]] All-American selection. He earned West Region Most Outstanding Player in the [[2018 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2018 NCAA Basketball Tournament]] for the [[2017\u201318 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2017\u201318 team]] that won the [[2018 Big Ten Conference Men's Basketball Tournament]] and reached the [[2018 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Championship Game|2018 NCAA Championship Game]]. After playing his [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirt]] junior season for the [[2018\u201319 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2018\u201319 Wolverines]], he declared for the [[2019 NBA Draft]].\n\n==Early life==\nMatthews was raised in the [[Avalon Park, Chicago|Avalon Park]]  [[Community areas of Chicago|Community area of Chicago]],<ref name=KtCMwgtbnMbs/> near 79th Street and Cottage Grove Avenue,<ref name=SRCMDSBBPotY/> which is on the borderline between the [[Chatham, Chicago|Chatham]] and [[Greater Grand Crossing, Chicago|Greater Grand Crossing]] Community areas on the [[South Side, Chicago|South Side]].<ref name=SRCMDSBBPotY/> Matthews briefly lived in [[Matteson, Illinois]] before returning to the South Side where he attended Ray Elementary and began his basketball career at the 63rd and Stony Island [[YMCA]].<ref name=KtCMwgtbnMbs/> In his youth, he played chess, hockey,<ref name=KtCMwgtbnMbs/> the [[trombone]] and [[skateboard]]ed, but he began to take basketball seriously the summer before his high school freshman year.<ref name=SRCMDSBBPotY/> Matthews committed to playing basketball for [[John Calipari]] and the [[Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball|Kentucky Wildcats]] on February 26, 2014 during his junior year. At the time, he was rated as the number 11 player and number 3 [[shooting guard]] in the national class of 2015 by [[Rivals.com]] and number 12 player by [[ESPN]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailyillini.com/uncategorized/2014/02/25/five-star-shooting-guard-charles-matthews-to-make-decision-wednesday/|title=Five-star shooting guard Charles Matthews to make decision Wednesday|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=February 25, 2014|work=[[The Daily Illini]]|author=Hettinger, Johnathan}}</ref><ref name=KL2FSCM>{{cite web|url=http://www.slamonline.com/college-hs/college/kentucky-lands-2015-five-star-sg-charles-matthews/#KlZULdXsBVIwx7Fz.97|title=Kentucky Lands 2015 Five-Star SG Charles Matthews|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=February 26, 2014|work=[[SLAM Magazine]]}}</ref> Among his other offers at the time were [[Illinois Fighting Illini men's basketball|Illinois]], [[Kansas Jayhawks men's basketball|Kansas]], [[Marquette Golden Eagles men's basketball|Marquette]] and [[Michigan State Spartans men's basketball|Michigan State]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2016/06/report_kentucky_transfer_charl.html|title=Report: Kentucky transfer Charles Matthews, a former top-100 recruit, considering Michigan|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=June 1, 2016|publisher=[[MLive.com]]|author=Quinn, Brendan F.}}</ref> Matthews was the first to commit to playing basketball for Kentucky's 2015 class.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbssports.com/college-basketball/news/comprehensive-breakdown-charles-matthews-commits-to-kentucky/|title=Comprehensive breakdown: Charles Matthews commits to Kentucky|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=February 26, 2014|work=[[CBS Sports]]|author=Borzello, Jeff}}</ref> On June 1, Matthews won the 2014 [[USA Basketball]] 3&ndash;on&ndash;3 Under-18 National Championship Tournament with teammates Braxton Blackwell, Tim Delaney and Kipper Nichols. Matthew earned the tournament's Most Valuable Player (MVP) award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usab.com/news-events/news/2014/06/us-youth-olympic-womens-basketball-team-named-after-completion-of-3x3-u18-national-championship.aspx|title=U.S. Youth Olympic Women's Team Named After 3x3 U18 National Championship Ends|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=June 1, 2014|publisher=[[USA Basketball]]}}</ref>\n\nMatthews officially signed his [[National Letter of Intent]] on National Signing Day, November 22, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/sports/signing-day-chicago-area-basketball-signees/|title=Signing Day: Chicago-area basketball signees|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=November 22, 2014|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|author=}}</ref> During Matthews' four-year high school career at St. Rita's, he led the team to 82 wins and four straight Chicago Catholic League South championships, including a 26&ndash;4 record as a senior.<ref name=SRCMDSBBPotY>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/suburbs/daily-southtown/sports/ct-sta-boys-basketball-player-of-year-charles-matthews-st-0328-20150327-story.html|title=St. Rita's Charles Matthews, Daily Southtown Boys Basketball Player of the Year|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=March 27, 2015|work=[[Daily Southtown]]|author=Disabato, Pat}}</ref> As a junior, he averaged 17.0 [[point (basketball)|points]] and 5.0 [[rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] for the 21&ndash;8 St. Rita's team that was eliminated from the 2014 [[Illinois High School Association|IHSA]] Class 4A playoffs by the [[Jahlil Okafor]]-led [[Whitney M. Young Magnet High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2014-03-14/sports/chi-jahlil-okafor-whitney-young-sectional-final-03-20140314_1_jahlil-okafor-charles-matthews-dominique-matthews|title=Jahlil Okafor, Young too much for St. Rita|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=March 14, 2014|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=Helfgot, Mike}}</ref><ref name=UofMBio/> As a senior, Matthews averaged 21.3 points and 6.2 rebounds and a 47 [[field goal percentage]].<ref name=SRCMDSBBPotY/><ref name=MAMWtR/> After his senior season, he was a selection for the [[Associated Press]]' Class-4A All-State first team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pjstar.com/article/20150319/SPORTS/150318927|title=Lots of stars, fewer spots on 3A/4A all-state teams|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=March 19, 2015|work=[[Peoria Journal Star]]}}</ref> Matthews' national ranking fell significantly from the time he committed to Kentucky to the end of his high school career.<ref>{{cite web|last=Roberts|first=Ben|url=http://www.kentucky.com/sports/college/kentucky-sports/uk-recruiting/article44594571.html|title=Though his stock has declined, skills of UK signee Matthews haven't, high school coach says|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=April 16, 2015|website=[[Kentucky.com]]}}</ref> Although his final rankings were 42nd by [[ESPN]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-sports/basketball/recruiting/player/_/id/144466/charles-matthews|title=Charles Matthews|accessdate=September 19, 2016|website=[[ESPN]]}}</ref> and 48th by [[Rivals.com]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://n.rivals.com/content/prospects/3893|title=Charles Matthews|accessdate=September 19, 2016|website=Rivals.com}}</ref> he graduated as the 59th ranked player according to 247Sports.com's composite ranking.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://247sports.com/Season/2015-Basketball/CompositeRecruitRankings?InstitutionGroup=HighSchool|title=2015 Top Basketball Recruits|accessdate=September 19, 2016|website=247Sports.com}}</ref>  Nonetheless, Matthews was selected to play in the 2015 [[Jordan Brand Classic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jordanbrandclassic.com/2015-all-american-boys-team-bios/|title=2015 All-American Boys Team Bios|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=|publisher=[[Jordan Brand Classic]]}}</ref> At Kentucky, he joined fellow Chicagoan and former [[Amateur Athletic Union|AAU]] teammate [[Tyler Ulis]] in the Kentucky backcourt.<ref name=KL2FSCM/>\n\n==College career==\n===Kentucky===\n[[File:Charles-Matthews.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Matthews with the [[2015\u201316 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team|2015\u201316 Wildcats]]]]\nMatthews played in 36 games (including 3 starting assignments) for the 2015\u201316 Kentucky Wildcats, posting averages of 1.7 points, 1.6 rebounds and 10.3 minutes.<ref name=SRgCMrtfKb/> Matthews' three starts included the season opener against [[2015\u201316 Albany Great Danes men's basketball team|Albany]] and the December 26 [[Kentucky\u2013Louisville rivalry|rivalry game]] against #16 ranked [[2015\u201316 Louisville Cardinals men's basketball team|Louisville]],<ref name=UofMBio/> when [[Isaiah Briscoe]] injured his ankle in pregame warmups and sat out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/ncb/recap/_/gameId/400814249|title=Tyler Ulis scores 21 as Kentucky holds off rival Louisville|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=December 26, 2015|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> His season highs were 11 points against [[2015\u201316 South Florida Bulls men's basketball team|South Florida]] (November 27),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/ncb/recap/_/gameId/400809389|title=Murray scores 21, No. 1 Kentucky rolls past USF 84-63|accessdate=March 20, 2018|date=November 27, 2015|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref> 7 rebounds against [[2015\u201316 Boston University Terriers men's basketball team|Boston University]] (November 24) and 34 minutes against [[2015\u201316 Illinois State Redbirds men's basketball team|Illinois State]] (November 30).<ref name=UofMBio/>\n\n===Michigan===\n[[File:20180206 UM-NW Charles Matthews 7DM27229.jpg|thumb|Matthews with the [[2017\u201318 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2017\u201318 Wolverines]]]]\nFollowing the season he had a medical procedure on his hip. Matthews was granted his release from the team on May 18, 2016.<ref name=SRgCMrtfKb>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/college/ct-st-rita-charles-matthews-transfer-kentucky-20160518-story.html|title=St. Rita grad Charles Matthews requests transfer from Kentucky basketball|accessdate=September 16, 2016|date=May 18, 2016|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|author=|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>  On June 20, 2016, reports confirmed that Matthews, who would have to sit out the 2016\u201317 season, had visited both [[Xavier Musketeers men's basketball|Xavier]] and Michigan and selected Michigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://collegebasketball.nbcsports.com/2016/06/20/report-michigan-lands-former-kentucky-guard-matthews/|title=Michigan lands former Kentucky guard Matthews|author=Johnson, Raphielle|publisher=[[NBC Sports]]|accessdate=June 21, 2016|date=June 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/id/16378757/charles-matthews-transferring-kentucky-wildcats-michigan-wolverines|title=Charles Matthews picks Michigan as transfer spot, source says|author=Goodman, Jeff|publisher=[[ESPN]]|accessdate=June 21, 2016|date=June 20, 2016}}</ref> Michigan confirmed the story on July 1.<ref name=MAMWtR>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/070116aaa.html|title=Michigan Adds Matthews, Wright-Jones to Roster|accessdate=July 13, 2016|date=July 1, 2016|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> He served on the scout team for the [[2016\u201317 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2016\u201317 Michigan Wolverines]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.michigandaily.com/section/mens-basketball/michigan%E2%80%99s-scout-team-gets-creative-simulating-oklahoma-state|title=Michigan\u2019s scout team gets creative simulating for Oklahoma State|accessdate=March 24, 2017|date=March 16, 2017|work=[[Michigan Daily]]|author=Carney, Brandon}}</ref>\n\n====Sophomore Year====\nAs a redshirt sophomore, Matthews scored 20 points against [[2017\u201318 North Florida Ospreys men's basketball team|North Florida]] in his first game at Michigan on November 11, 2017. In the game, he and [[Duncan Robinson (basketball)|Duncan Robinson]] became the first Michigan teammates to score 20 points in a game since March 3, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400986333|title=Michigan pulls away late for 86-66 win over North Florida|accessdate=November 12, 2017|date=November 11, 2017|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/news/2017/11/11/mens-basketball-wolverines-use-second-half-burst-to-down-north-florida-in-2017-18-opener.aspx|title=Wolverines Use Second-Half Burst to Down North Florida in 2017-18 Opener|accessdate=November 12, 2017|date=November 11, 2017|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> Matthews posted career-highs of 28 points and eight rebounds in the first-round game of the [[2017 Maui Invitational Tournament]] against [[2017\u201318 LSU Tigers basketball team|LSU]] on November 20  but only made one of two free throws with Michigan trailing by two points with 9 seconds remaining.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400986374|title=LSU rallies late for 77-75 win over Michigan in Maui|accessdate=November 21, 2017|date=November 21, 2017|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/news/2017/11/21/mens-basketball-wolverines-rally-against-lsu-falls-just-short-in-maui-opener.aspx|title=Wolverines' Rally Against LSU Falls Just Short in Maui Opener|accessdate=November 21, 2017|date=November 21, 2017|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> The following night, he posted his first career [[double-double]] with 22 points (on 8-of-8 [[field goal (basketball)|field goal]] shooting) and 10 rebounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401000094|title=Michigan rolls over Chaminade 102-64 at Maui Invitational|accessdate=November 22, 2017|date=November 21, 2017|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/news/2017/11/21/mens-basketball-michigan-rolls-past-chaminade-at-maui-invitational.aspx|title=Michigan Rolls Past Chaminade at Maui Invitational|accessdate=November 22, 2017|date=November 21, 2017|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> On November 26, Matthews posted a points-[[assist (basketball)|assists]] double-double with 17 points and a career-high 12 assists against [[2017\u201318 UC Riverside Highlanders men's basketball team|UC Riverside]]. Since [[Moe Wagner]] added 21 points and 10 rebounds, the team had its first pair of double-doubles in a game since [[Glenn Robinson III]] and [[Trey Burke]] did so for the [[2012\u201313 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2012\u201313 National Runner-up Wolverines]] on January 6, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=400986393|title=Wagner's double-double leads Michigan past UC Riverside,|accessdate=November 27, 2017|date=November 26, 2017|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/news/2017/11/26/mens-basketball-wolverines-dominate-uc-riverside-in-wire-to-wire-win.aspx|title=Wolverines Dominate UC Riverside in Wire-to-Wire Win|accessdate=November 27, 2017|date=November 26, 2017|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> On December 21, Michigan defeated the previously winless [[2017\u201318 Alabama A&M Bulldogs basketball team|Alabama A&M Bulldogs]] 97&ndash;47 as Matthews posted 31 points, another career high.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/boxscore?gameId=400986453|title=Matthews leads Michigan past winless Alabama A&M, 97-47|accessdate=December 22, 2017|date=December 21, 2017|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/news/2017/12/21/mens-basketball-matthews-career-day-propels-u-m-past-alabama-am.aspx|title=Matthews' Career Day Propels U-M Past Alabama A&M|accessdate=December 22, 2017|date=December 21, 2017|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com}}</ref> Matthews tallied 20 or more points six different times before the final four, but none in [[2017\u201318 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season|2017\u201318 Big Ten Conference play]], where he never scored more than 16 points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/more/la-sp-ncaa-west-sidebar-20180324-story.html|title=Charles Matthews steps up for the Wolverines in regional final|accessdate=March 27, 2018|date=March 24, 2018|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Fenno, Nathan}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2018/03/john_calipari_has_high_praise.html|title=John Calipari has high praise for Charles Matthews after West Region honor|accessdate=March 27, 2018|date=March 26, 2018|website=[[MLive.com]]|author=Slagter, Josh}}</ref>\n\nMatthews averaged 10 points and 5.5 rebounds during Michigan's four games in the [[2018 Big Ten Conference Men's Basketball Tournament]],<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180305061946/http://www.bigten.org/library/stats/mbb-tournament.pdf|url=http://www.bigten.org/library/stats/mbb-tournament.pdf|title=2018 Big Ten Men's Basketball Tournament Statistics|accessdate=March 5, 2018|archivedate=March 5, 2018|date=March 4, 2018|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=BigTen.org}}</ref> helping the team win its second consecutive Big Ten  Tournament Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401020042|title=Michigan beats Purdue to win 2nd straight Big Ten Tournament|accessdate=March 4, 2018|date=March 4, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgoblue.com/news/2018/3/4/mens-basketball-back-to-back-wagner-teske-power-michigan-to-second-straight-b1g-tournament-title.aspx|title=Back-to-Back: Wagner, Teske Power Michigan to Second Straight B1G Tournament Title|accessdate=March 4, 2018|date=March 4, 2018|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> On March 15, Michigan began play in the [[2018 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2018 NCAA Tournament]] with a  61&ndash;47 victory over [[2017\u201318 Montana Grizzlies basketball team|Montana]] in the first round, as Matthews posted 20 points and a career-tying 11 rebounds, for his fourth double-double of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401025838|title=Michigan plods to 61-47 win over Montana in NCAA first round|accessdate=March 16, 2018|date=March 16, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgoblue.com/news/2018/3/16/mens-basketball-michigan-eases-into-ncaa-second-round-with-win-over-montana.aspx|title=Michigan Eases into NCAA First Round with Win Over Montana|accessdate=March 16, 2018|date=March 16, 2018|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> On March 21, Matthews became an Academic All-Big Ten honoree.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgoblue.com/news/2018/3/21/general-winter-academic-all-big-ten-selections-announced.aspx|title=Winter Academic All-Big Ten Selections Announced|accessdate=March 29, 2018|date=March 21, 2018|website=MGoBlue.com|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|author=Blevins, Ben}}</ref> On March 24, Michigan defeated [[2017\u201318 Florida State Seminoles men's basketball team|Florida State]] 58&ndash;54 in the West regional finals. Michigan, who established a single-season school record  32 wins with the win, was led by Matthews with 17 points. Matthews, who averaged 16.5 points and 7.3 rebounds to lead Michigan in the first four games of the NCAA tournament, was named West Region Most Outstanding player.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgoblue.com/news/2018/3/26/mens-basketball-two-streaks-collide-wolverines-to-face-ramblers-in-ncaa-semifinal.aspx|title=Two Streaks Collide: Wolverines to Face Ramblers in NCAA Semifinal|accessdate=March 29, 2018|date=March 26, 2018|website=MGoBlue.com|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401025885|title=Oh Blue!: Michigan nips Florida St 58-54 to reach Final Four|accessdate=March 25, 2018|date=March 24, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgoblue.com/news/2018/3/24/mens-basketball-hello-final-four-michigans-defense-reigns-against-florida-state.aspx|title=Hello, Final Four! Michigan's Defense Reigns Against Florida State|accessdate=March 25, 2018|date=March 24, 2018|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> On March 31 in the national semifinals, Matthews contributed 17 as Michigan defeated [[2017\u201318 Loyola Ramblers men's basketball team|Loyola\u2013Chicago]] 69&ndash;57.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401025887|title=Wagner, Michigan end Loyola's run 69-57 in Final Four|accessdate=March 31, 2018|date=March 31, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgoblue.com/news/2018/3/31/mens-basketball-wolverines-take-down-loyola-chicago-to-advance-to-ncaa-championship-game.aspx|title=Wolverines Take Down Loyola Chicago to Advance to NCAA Championship Game|accessdate=March 31, 2018|date=March 31, 2018|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/04/01/larry-bird-hakeem-olajuwon-would-know-how-good-moe-wagner-was/|title=Larry Bird, Hakeem Olajuwon would know how good Moe Wagner was|accessdate=April 1, 2018|date=April 1, 2018|work=[[New York Post]]|first=Howie|last=Kussoy}}</ref> The team lost in the [[2018 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Championship Game]] to (#2 Coaches Poll/#2 AP Poll)  [[2017\u201318 Villanova Wildcats men's basketball team|Villanova]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401025888|title=Villanova takes title, 79-62 over Michigan behind DiVincenzo|accessdate=April 3, 2018|date=April 3, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mgoblue.com/news/2018/4/2/mens-basketball-michigan-comes-up-short-against-villanova-in-national-championship-game.aspx|title=Michigan Comes Up Short Against Villanova in National Championship Game|accessdate=April 3, 2018|date=April 2, 2018|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> For the tournament he averaged 14.8 points, 6.2 rebounds, 1.2 assists, and 1.2 steals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2767906-march-madness-2018-the-all-tournament-team-after-the-national-championship|title=March Madness 2018: The All-Tournament Team After the National Championship|accessdate=April 5, 2018|date=April 3, 2018|publisher=[[Bleacher Report]]|author=Miller, Kerry}}</ref> For the season, he averaged 13.0 points and 5.5 rebounds.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/sports/college/university-michigan/2018/04/03/moritz-wagner-charles-matthews-have-decisions-make-nba-draft/33501655/|title=Moritz Wagner, Charles Matthews have decisions to make about NBA Draft|accessdate=April 5, 2018|date=April 3, 2018|work=[[Detroit News]]|author=Hawkins, James}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the season he declared for the [[2018 NBA draft]] without hiring an agent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/23262732/charles-matthews-michigan-wolverwines-entering-draft-agent|title=Michigan's Charles Matthews to test NBA draft waters|accessdate=April 20, 2018|date=April 20, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]|author=Borzello, Jeff}}</ref> He didn't received an invitation to the [[NBA Draft combine]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/sports/college/university-michigan/2018/05/01/report-matthews-wagner-invited-nba-combine/34439667/|title=Report: Matthews, Wagner invited to NBA Combine|accessdate=May 3, 2018|date=May 1, 2018|work=[[Detroit News]]|author=Hawkins, James}}</ref> Nonetheless, he had workouts with multiple NBA teams.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nba.com/nuggets/story/matthews-harris-chat-052218|title=Michigan's Charles Matthews In For Pre-Draft Workout, Chats With Gary Harris|accessdate=May 30, 2018|date=May 22, 2018|publisher=[[NBA.com]]|author=Dempsey, Christopher}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://dailyknicks.com/2018/05/28/new-york-knicks-host-charles-matthews-pre-draft-workout/|title=New York Knicks host Charles Matthews for pre-draft workout|accessdate=May 30, 2018|date=May 29, 2018|publisher=[[Fansided]]|website=Dailyknicks.com|author=Ogden, Maxwell}}</ref> In the 2017 draft class, 84 of the 137 underclassmen that declared were not invited to the NBA draft combine and only 4 remained in the draft. None of the four was drafted in the [[2017 NBA draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/wolverines/index.ssf/2018/05/with_decision_deadline_looming.html|title=With deadline looming, no word yet if Charles Matthews will pick NBA or Michigan|accessdate=May 30, 2018|date=May 23, 2018|work=[[MLive.com]]|author=Kahn, Andrew}}</ref> Matthews withdrew from the 2018 NBA draft.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/ncaa-basketball/news/nba-draft-2018-charles-matthews-withdraws-name-returns-to-michigan/an32eeeyetii1ac65rzjsrm58|title=NBA Draft 2018: Charles Matthews withdraws name, returns to Michigan|accessdate=May 31, 2018|date=May 30, 2018|work=[[Sporting News]]|author=Brzezinski, Alec}}</ref>\n\n====Junior year====\n[[File:20181204 Charles Matthews at UM-NW game (11).jpg|thumb|left|Matthews for the [[2018\u201319 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|2018\u201319 Wolverines]]]]\nMatthews was a preseason All-Big Ten selection by the Big Ten Media.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bigten.org/news/2018/10/11/big-ten-mens-basketball-basketball-preseason-honors-announced.aspx?path=mbball|title=Big Ten Men\u2019s Basketball Basketball Preseason Honors Announced|accessdate=October 15, 2018|date=October 11, 2018|website=BigTen.org|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> Prior to the season he was one of nine Big Ten players named to the preseason [[John R. Wooden Award]] watchlist and one of eight named to the preseason [[Naismith College Player of the Year]] watchlist.<ref name=WApt5a>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/story/_/page/woodenwatch110618/college-basketball-2018-wooden-watch-list-announced|title=Wooden Award preseason top 50 announced|accessdate=November 7, 2018|date=November 6, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://naismithtrophy.com/citizen-naismith-trophy-mens-watch-list-released/|title=Citizen Naismith Trophy Men\u2019s Watch List Released {{!}} Citizen Naismith Trophy|website=naismithtrophy.com|language=en-US|access-date=November 9, 2018}}</ref> On December 15, Michigan defeated [[2018\u201319 Western Michigan Broncos men's basketball team|Western Michigan]] 70&ndash;62 with 25 points and 10 rebounds from Matthews, for his fifth career double-double and first of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082455|title=No. 5 Michigan beats Western Michigan 70-62, stays unbeaten|accessdate=December 15, 2018|date=December 15, 2018|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2018/12/15/mens-basketball-matthews-double-double-lifts-wolverines-to-win-over-upstart-wmu.aspx|title=Matthews' Double-Double Lifts Wolverines to Win Over Upstart WMU|accessdate=December 15, 2018|date=December 15, 2018|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref>  On January 13, Michigan defeated [[2018\u201319 Northwestern Wildcats men's basketball team|Northwestern]] to establish a school record for best start at 17&ndash;0 and tied the school's record 17-game win streak.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082459|title=No. 2 Michigan now 17-0 after 80-60 win over Northwestern|accessdate=January 14, 2019|date=January 13, 2019|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/1/13/mens-basketball-career-nights-from-simpson-teske-spark-u-m-to-victory-program-best-17-0-start.aspx|title=Career Nights from Simpson, Teske Spark U-M to Victory, Program-Best 17-0 Start|accessdate=January 14, 2019|date=January 13, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> On January 22, Michigan defeated [[2018\u201319 Minnesota Golden Gophers men's basketball team|Minnesota]] 59&ndash;57 after a [[buzzer beater]] by Matthews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082461|title=Matthews beats buzzer, No. 5 Michigan edges Minnesota 59-57|accessdate=January 22, 2019|date=January 22, 2019|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/1/22/mens-basketball-matthews-buzzer-beater-puts-emphatic-end-to-minnesotas-upset-bid.aspx|title=Matthews' Buzzer Beater Puts Emphatic End to Minnesota's Upset Bid|accessdate=January 22, 2019|date=January 22, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> On January 25, Matthews posted 10 points and a career-tying 11 rebounds for his sixth career double-double in a 69\u201346 victory over Indiana.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082380|title=No. 5 Michigan keeps rolling with 69-46 win at Indiana|accessdate=January 25, 2019|date=January 25, 2019|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/1/25/mens-basketball-wolverines-jump-out-to-big-early-lead-roll-to-victory-over-hoosiers.aspx|title=Wolverines Jump Out to Big Early Lead, Roll to Victory Over Hoosiers|accessdate=January 25, 2019|date=January 25, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> The 23-point victory marked the largest ever by Michigan on the road against Indiana.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/1/28/2018-19-michigan-mens-basketball-awards-and-honors.aspx?path=mbball|title=Awards & Honors: Brazdeikis Tabbed B1G Freshman of the Week|accessdate=January 28, 2019|date=January 28, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190129064213/https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/1/28/2018-19-michigan-mens-basketball-awards-and-honors.aspx?path=mbball|archive-date=January 29, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref> On February 6, Matthews was the only Big Ten Athlete named a [[Julius Erving Award]] Top 10 finalist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hoophall.com/news/naismith-memorial-basketball-hall-of-fame-narrows-watch-list-for-2019-julius-erving-award|title=Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame Narrows Watch List for 2019 Julius Erving Award|accessdate=February 6, 2019|date=February 6, 2019|publisher=[[Naismith Basketball Hall of Fame]]}}</ref>  On February 9, Michigan defeated (#19/#19) [[2018\u201319 Wisconsin Badgers men's basketball team|Wisconsin]] 61&ndash;52. Michigan was led by Matthews with a game-high 18 points. The teams each scored 27 in the first half and 16 of Matthews 18 came in the second half, including 14 of Michigan's 19 points in a decisive stretch taking the score from 38&ndash;35 to 57&ndash;50 with 23.8 seconds remaining.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401082464|title=No. 7 Michigan outlasts No. 19 Wisconsin 61-52|accessdate=February 9, 2019|date=February 9, 2019|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/2/9/mens-basketball-matthews-second-half-scoring-outburst-lifts-u-m-past-no-19-wisconsin.aspx|title=Matthews' Second-Half Scoring Outburst Lifts U-M Past No. 19 Wisconsin|accessdate=February 9, 2019|date=February 9, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> Matthews missed the final three games of the regular season due to an ankle injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/3/9/mens-basketball-michigan-falls-to-michigan-state-in-regular-season-finale.aspx|title=Michigan Falls to Michigan State in Regular-Season Finale|accessdate=March 12, 2019|date=March 9, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> Following the season, he was a [[2018\u201319 Big Ten Conference men's basketball season|2019]] All-[[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]] honorable mention selection (media).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bigten.org/news/2019/3/11/big-ten-unveils-mens-basketball-postseason-honors-on-btn.aspx|title=Big Ten Unveils Men\u2019s Basketball Postseason Honors on BTN|accessdate=March 11, 2019|date=March 11, 2019|website=BigTen.org|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/3/11/mens-basketball-brazdeikis-top-big-ten-freshman-joins-simpson-as-all-b1g-second-teamers.aspx|title=Brazdeikis Top Big Ten Freshman, Joins Simpson on All-B1G Second Team|accessdate=March 11, 2019|date=March 11, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wyrot, Tom}}</ref> On March 21, Matthews posted a game-high 22 points points and ten rebounds for his seventh career double-double in a 74&ndash;55 victory over [[2018\u201319 Montana Grizzlies basketball team|Montana]] in the first round of the [[2019 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|2019 NCAA Tournament]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mens-college-basketball/recap?gameId=401123405|title=Matthews' double-double leads Michigan past Grizzlies, 74-53|accessdate=March 22, 2019|date=March 22, 2019|publisher=[[ESPN]]|agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/3/21/mens-basketball-michigan-marches-on-after-rolling-past-montana-in-ncaa-tournament.aspx|title=Michigan Marches on After Rolling Past Montana in NCAA Tournament|accessdate=March 22, 2019|date=March 22, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wywrot, Tom}}</ref> Following the season, on April 9, 2019, Matthews (along with teammates [[Iggy Brazdeikis]] and [[Jordan Poole]]) declared for the [[2019 NBA draft]] with the intention of hiring agents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mgoblue.com/news/2019/4/9/mens-basketball-matthews-poole-and-brazdeikis-to-declare-for-early-entry-into-nba-draft.aspx|title=Matthews, Poole and Brazdeikis to Declare for Early Entry into NBA Draft|accessdate=April 9, 2019|date=April 9, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|website=MGoBlue.com|author=Wywrot, Tom}}</ref> On April 17, Matthews announced, via the Michigan basketball [[Twitter]] account, that he would forgo his remaining year of eligibility at Michigan.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/sports/college/university-michigan/2019/04/17/michigan-wolverines-charles-matthews-tostay-nba-draft/3498776002/|title=Michigan's Charles Matthews to forgo final season, stay in NBA draft|accessdate=April 18, 2019|date=April 17, 2019|work=[[Detroit News]]|author=Hawkins, James}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://nbc25news.com/sports/college/charles-matthews-officially-departs-michigan-for-nba|title=Charles Matthews officially departs Michigan for NBA|accessdate=April 18, 2019|date=April 17, 2019|work=[[WEYI-TV]]|author=Trotman, Jeanna}}</ref>\n\nOn June 9, 2019, Matthews tore his anterior cruciate ligament during a predraft workout with the Boston Celtics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/nba-draft-prospect-charles-matthews-tears-acl-during-celtics-workout-no-timetable-set-for-his-return/|title=NBA Draft prospect Charles Matthews tears ACL during Celtics workout; no timetable set for his return|accessdate=June 24, 2019|date=June 10, 2019|publisher=[[CBS Sports]]|author=Siddiqi, DJ}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMatthews' parents are Nichole and Charles Matthews who met at [[Southern Illinois University]].<ref name=UofMBio>{{cite web|url=http://www.mgoblue.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/charles_matthews_1018904.html|title=Charles Matthews 1|accessdate=September 19, 2016|date=|website=MGoBlue.com|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref> His older brother, Dominique, was a St. Rita's teammate until he graduated in 2014.<ref name=SRCMDSBBPotY/> Dominique went on to play for the [[UIC Flames men's basketball|UIC Flames]].<ref name=UofMBio/> His younger brother, Jordan, was four classes behind Charles at St. Rita's.<ref name=KtCMwgtbnMbs>{{cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/sports/college/university-michigan/wolverines/2017/05/28/michigan-wolverines-basketball-charles-matthews/326067001/|title=How Kentucky transfer Charles Matthews was groomed to be next Michigan basketball star|accessdate=February 7, 2018|date=May 27, 2017 |work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|author=Snyder, Mark}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n|style=\"background:#CFECEC; width:1em\"|*\n|Led NCAA Division I\n|}\n\n===College===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2015\u201316 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2015\u201316]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2015\u201316 Kentucky Wildcats men's basketball team|Kentucky]]\n| 36 || 3 || 10.3 || .442 || .250 || .412 || 1.6 || .4 || .4 || .2 || 1.7\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2017\u201318]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2017\u201318 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|Michigan]]\n| style=\"background:#cfecec;\"| '''41'''* || style=\"background:#cfecec;\"| '''41'''* || 30.1 || '''.495''' || '''.318''' || .558 || '''5.5''' || '''2.4''' || .7 || '''.6''' || '''13.0'''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 NCAA Division I men's basketball season|2018\u201319]]\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2018\u201319 Michigan Wolverines men's basketball team|Michigan]]\n| 34 || 34 || '''31.5''' || .431 || .299 || '''.645''' || 5.0 || 1.4 || '''1.1''' || .5 || 12.2\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" colspan=\"2\"| Career\n| 111 || 78 || 24.1 || .464 || .308 || .576 || 4.1 || 1.4 || .7 || .4 || 9.1\n{{S-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}